WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:04:16.507 --> 00:04:19.927
<i>This is a story
of an ordinary little boy...</i>

3
00:04:20.094 --> 00:04:23.139
<i>...named Charlie Bucket.</i>

4
00:04:23.806 --> 00:04:28.352
<i>He was not faster or stronger
or more clever than other children.</i>

5
00:04:30.312 --> 00:04:35.109
<i>His family was not rich
or powerful or well-connected.</i>

6
00:04:35.276 --> 00:04:39.071
<i>In fact. they barely had enough to eat.</i>

7
00:04:40.114 --> 00:04:44.535
<i>Charlie Bucket was the luckiest boy
in the entire world.</i>

8
00:04:44.702 --> 00:04:47.079
<i>He just didn't know it yet.</i>

9
00:05:04.013 --> 00:05:05.681
- Evening. Buckets.
- Evening.

10
00:05:05.848 --> 00:05:07.308
Hi. Dad.

11
00:05:09.393 --> 00:05:11.645
Soup's almost ready. darling.

12
00:05:12.229 --> 00:05:15.483
Don't suppose there's anything
extra to put in. love.

13
00:05:16.275 --> 00:05:18.944
Oh. well. Nothing goes better
with cabbage than cabbage.

14
00:05:23.491 --> 00:05:24.950
Charlie...

15
00:05:25.409 --> 00:05:27.870
...I found something I think you'll like.

16
00:05:31.081 --> 00:05:35.377
<i>Charlie's father worked
at the local toothpaste factory.</i>

17
00:05:35.544 --> 00:05:39.590
<i>The hours were long.
and the pay was terrible...</i>

18
00:05:39.757 --> 00:05:44.595
<i>...yet occasionally.
there were unexpected surprises.</i>

19
00:05:47.097 --> 00:05:48.599
It's exactly what I need.

20
00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:51.227
What is it. Charlie?

21
00:05:57.274 --> 00:05:59.777
Dad found it. just the piece I needed.

22
00:05:59.944 --> 00:06:02.947
- What piece was it?
- A head for Willy Wonka.

23
00:06:03.113 --> 00:06:04.365
Well. how wonderful.

24
00:06:04.532 --> 00:06:06.575
It's quite a likeness.

25
00:06:06.742 --> 00:06:08.410
- You think so?
- Think so?

26
00:06:08.577 --> 00:06:10.162
I know so.

27
00:06:10.329 --> 00:06:13.999
I saw Willy Wonka
with my own two eyes.

28
00:06:14.166 --> 00:06:16.460
- I used to work for him. you know.
- You did?

29
00:06:16.627 --> 00:06:18.170
- I did.
- He did.

30
00:06:18.462 --> 00:06:19.630
He did.

31
00:06:19.797 --> 00:06:21.799
I love grapes.

32
00:06:22.132 --> 00:06:26.345
Of course. I was a much
younger man in those days.

33
00:06:27.638 --> 00:06:32.393
<i>Willy Wonka began with
a single store on Cherry Street.</i>

34
00:06:32.601 --> 00:06:35.854
<i>But the whole world wanted his candy.</i>

35
00:06:39.316 --> 00:06:41.569
- Mr. Wonka.
- Yeah?

36
00:06:41.735 --> 00:06:43.529
We need more Wonka bars...

37
00:06:43.696 --> 00:06:47.533
- ...and we're out of chocolate birds.
- Birds?

38
00:06:47.825 --> 00:06:49.159
Birds.

39
00:06:49.326 --> 00:06:53.372
Well. then we'll need
to make some more. Here.

40
00:06:56.041 --> 00:06:57.710
Now open.

41
00:07:01.839 --> 00:07:03.966
The man was a genius.

42
00:07:04.466 --> 00:07:08.804
Did you know he invented a new way
of making chocolate ice cream...

43
00:07:08.971 --> 00:07:12.641
...so that it stays cold for hours
without a freezer?

44
00:07:12.808 --> 00:07:17.313
You can even leave it lying in the sun
on a hot day. and it won't go runny.

45
00:07:18.188 --> 00:07:21.358
- But that's impossible.
- But Willy Wonka did it.

46
00:07:24.403 --> 00:07:25.738
<i>Before long...</i>

47
00:07:25.904 --> 00:07:29.450
<i>...he decided to build
a proper chocolate factory.</i>

48
00:07:29.617 --> 00:07:32.703
<i>The largest chocolate factory
in history.</i>

49
00:07:32.870 --> 00:07:36.165
<i>Fifty times as big as any other.</i>

50
00:07:55.184 --> 00:07:56.852
Grandpa. don't make it gross.

51
00:07:57.936 --> 00:08:01.732
Tell him about the Indian prince.
He'd like to hear about that.

52
00:08:02.274 --> 00:08:04.568
You mean. Prince Pondicherry?

53
00:08:05.235 --> 00:08:09.531
Well. Prince Pondicherry
wrote a letter to Mr. Wonka...

54
00:08:09.907 --> 00:08:12.409
...and asked him to come
all the way out to India...

55
00:08:12.868 --> 00:08:17.206
...and build him a colossal palace
entirely out of chocolate.

56
00:08:20.417 --> 00:08:21.877
It will have 100 rooms...

57
00:08:22.044 --> 00:08:26.674
...and everything will be made
of dark or light chocolate.

58
00:08:29.718 --> 00:08:33.138
<i>True to his word.
the bricks were chocolate...</i>

59
00:08:33.305 --> 00:08:36.058
<i>...and the cement holding
them together was chocolate.</i>

60
00:08:36.767 --> 00:08:40.104
<i>All the walls and ceilings
were made of chocolate as well.</i>

61
00:08:41.480 --> 00:08:44.858
<i>So were the carpets
and the pictures and the furniture.</i>

62
00:08:45.025 --> 00:08:47.945
It is perfect in every way.

63
00:08:48.112 --> 00:08:51.240
Yeah. but it won't last long.
You better start eating right now.

64
00:08:51.407 --> 00:08:55.202
Oh. nonsense. I will not eat my palace.

65
00:08:55.369 --> 00:08:58.706
I intend to live in it.

66
00:09:01.458 --> 00:09:03.961
<i>But Mr. Wonka was right. of course.</i>

67
00:09:04.628 --> 00:09:09.800
<i>Soon after this. there came
a very hot day with a boiling sun.</i>

68
00:09:11.051 --> 00:09:13.053
Mmm.

69
00:09:46.003 --> 00:09:50.716
<i>The prince sent an urgent telegram
requesting a new palace...</i>

70
00:09:50.883 --> 00:09:53.677
<i>...but Willy Wonka was facing
problems of his own.</i>

71
00:09:55.679 --> 00:10:00.559
<i>All the other chocolate makers. you see.
had grown jealous of Mr. Wonka.</i>

72
00:10:00.726 --> 00:10:05.522
<i>They began sending in spies
to steal his secret recipes.</i>

73
00:10:33.342 --> 00:10:37.387
<i>Fickelgruber started making
an ice cream that would never melt.</i>

74
00:10:37.554 --> 00:10:41.934
<i>Prodnose came out with a chewing gum
that never lost its flavor.</i>

75
00:10:42.100 --> 00:10:44.895
<i>Then Slugworth
began making candy balloons...</i>

76
00:10:45.062 --> 00:10:48.065
<i>...that you could blow up
to incredible sizes.</i>

77
00:10:48.982 --> 00:10:51.193
<i>The thievery got so bad...</i>

78
00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:53.529
<i>...that one day. without warning...</i>

79
00:10:53.695 --> 00:10:58.242
<i>...Mr. Wonka told every single one
of his workers to go home.</i>

80
00:10:58.408 --> 00:11:03.247
<i>He announced that he was closing
his chocolate factory forever.</i>

81
00:11:03.413 --> 00:11:07.626
I'm closing my chocolate factory
forever.

82
00:11:07.793 --> 00:11:09.086
I'm sorry.

83
00:11:25.769 --> 00:11:28.814
But it didn't close forever.
It's open right now.

84
00:11:28.981 --> 00:11:33.235
Ah. yes. sometimes when grownups say
"forever." they mean "a very long time."

85
00:11:33.902 --> 00:11:37.114
Such as. "I feel like I've eaten
nothing but cabbage soup forever."

86
00:11:37.447 --> 00:11:40.951
- Now. Pops.
- The factory did close. Charlie.

87
00:11:41.118 --> 00:11:45.122
And it seemed like it was
going to be closed forever.

88
00:11:45.289 --> 00:11:49.960
Then one day we saw smoke
rising from the chimneys.

89
00:11:50.127 --> 00:11:54.006
- The factory was back in business.
- Did you get your job back?

90
00:11:54.840 --> 00:11:56.300
No.

91
00:11:56.466 --> 00:11:58.302
No one did.

92
00:12:01.763 --> 00:12:03.599
But there must be
people working there.

93
00:12:03.932 --> 00:12:07.311
Think about it. Charlie.
Have you ever seen a single person...

94
00:12:07.477 --> 00:12:10.147
...going into that factory
or coming out of it?

95
00:12:11.607 --> 00:12:14.526
No. The gates are always closed.

96
00:12:14.693 --> 00:12:16.361
Exactly.

97
00:12:16.945 --> 00:12:19.031
But then. who's running the machines?

98
00:12:19.197 --> 00:12:22.159
- Nobody knows. Charlie.
- It certainly is a mystery.

99
00:12:22.868 --> 00:12:24.661
Hasn't someone asked Mr. Wonka?

100
00:12:25.704 --> 00:12:29.374
Nobody sees him anymore.
He never comes out.

101
00:12:30.167 --> 00:12:34.463
The only thing that comes
out of that place is the candy...

102
00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:37.174
...already packed and addressed.

103
00:12:37.799 --> 00:12:42.763
I'd give anything in the world
just to go in one more time...

104
00:12:42.930 --> 00:12:47.017
...and see what's become
of that amazing factory.

105
00:12:48.018 --> 00:12:51.563
Well. you won't. because you can't.
No one can.

106
00:12:52.022 --> 00:12:55.692
It's a mystery.
and it will always be a mystery.

107
00:12:56.151 --> 00:13:00.656
That little factory of yours. Charlie. is as
close as any of us is ever going to get.

108
00:13:02.366 --> 00:13:06.036
Come on. Charlie. I think it's time
we let your grandparents get some sleep.

109
00:13:08.497 --> 00:13:11.291
- Good night. Grandpa George.
- Night. Charlie.

110
00:13:11.458 --> 00:13:13.543
- Night-night.
- Chair.

111
00:13:13.710 --> 00:13:15.587
Thank you. dear.

112
00:13:17.214 --> 00:13:19.007
Night. Grandpa Joe.

113
00:13:20.884 --> 00:13:22.719
Good night. Grandma Georgina.

114
00:13:22.886 --> 00:13:26.056
Nothing's impossible. Charlie.

115
00:13:43.115 --> 00:13:45.534
- Good night.
- Night. Charlie.

116
00:13:45.701 --> 00:13:47.285
Sleep well.

117
00:13:57.838 --> 00:13:59.965
<i>indeed. that very night...</i>

118
00:14:00.132 --> 00:14:03.593
<i>...the impossible
had already been set in motion.</i>

119
00:14:03.593 --> 00:14:33.593
<b>Subtitle | www.movieddl.me</b>

120
00:15:04.154 --> 00:15:06.281
<i>Dear people of the world...</i>

121
00:15:06.656 --> 00:15:08.200
<i>...I. Willy Wonka...</i>

122
00:15:08.575 --> 00:15:12.996
<i>...have decided to allow five children
to visit my factory this year.</i>

123
00:15:13.163 --> 00:15:16.833
<i>In addition. one of these children
shall receive a special prize...</i>

124
00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.587
<i>...beyond anything
you could ever imagine.</i>

125
00:15:21.129 --> 00:15:23.006
Five golden tickets have been hidden...

126
00:15:23.173 --> 00:15:26.510
...underneath the ordinary wrapping
paper of five ordinary Wonka bars.

127
00:15:26.885 --> 00:15:28.887
The bars may be anywhere...

128
00:15:29.054 --> 00:15:34.810
...in any shop. in any street. in any
town. in any country in the world.

129
00:16:09.219 --> 00:16:12.764
Wouldn't it be something. Charlie.
to open a bar of candy...

130
00:16:12.931 --> 00:16:15.350
...and find a golden ticket inside?

131
00:16:15.684 --> 00:16:20.230
I know. but I only get one bar a year.
for my birthday.

132
00:16:20.397 --> 00:16:22.065
Well. it's your birthday next week.

133
00:16:22.649 --> 00:16:25.694
You have as much chance
as anybody does.

134
00:16:25.861 --> 00:16:28.905
Balderdash. The kids who are
going to find the golden tickets...

135
00:16:29.072 --> 00:16:31.908
...are the ones who can afford
to buy candy bars every day.

136
00:16:32.075 --> 00:16:35.996
Our Charlie gets only one a year.
He doesn't have a chance.

137
00:16:36.329 --> 00:16:38.790
Everyone has a chance. Charlie.

138
00:16:39.207 --> 00:16:42.919
Mark my words.
the kid who finds the first ticket...

139
00:16:43.086 --> 00:16:45.463
...will be fat. fat. fat.

140
00:16:46.131 --> 00:16:47.883
Augustus. This way.

141
00:16:52.846 --> 00:16:54.806
I am eating the Wonka bar...

142
00:16:54.973 --> 00:16:58.268
...and I taste something
that is not chocolate...

143
00:16:59.186 --> 00:17:01.062
<i>...or coconut...</i>

144
00:17:01.646 --> 00:17:03.940
...or walnut or peanut butter...

145
00:17:04.441 --> 00:17:06.359
<i>...or nougat...</i>

146
00:17:06.776 --> 00:17:11.281
...or butter brittle
or caramel or sprinkles.

147
00:17:12.699 --> 00:17:14.492
<i>So I look...</i>

148
00:17:15.911 --> 00:17:17.454
...and I find the golden ticket.

149
00:17:17.621 --> 00:17:19.789
Augustus. how did you celebrate?

150
00:17:20.457 --> 00:17:22.709
I eat more candy.

151
00:17:25.962 --> 00:17:28.798
We knew Augustus would find
the golden ticket.

152
00:17:29.466 --> 00:17:31.718
He eats so many candy bars a day...

153
00:17:31.885 --> 00:17:35.639
...that it was not possible
for him not to find one.

154
00:17:35.805 --> 00:17:38.975
Yes. it is good. Augustus.

155
00:17:39.184 --> 00:17:41.394
<i>golden ticket claimed and four more...</i>

156
00:17:41.603 --> 00:17:43.146
Told you it'd be a porker.

157
00:17:43.563 --> 00:17:45.440
What a repulsive boy.

158
00:17:45.857 --> 00:17:47.525
Only four golden tickets left.

159
00:17:47.734 --> 00:17:52.322
Now that they've found one.
things will really get crazy.

160
00:17:52.489 --> 00:17:54.491
- <i>-Of every shape. size and hue.</i>

161
00:17:58.453 --> 00:18:01.081
Veruca.
Can you spell that for us. please?

162
00:18:01.248 --> 00:18:04.793
V-E-R-U-C-A. Veruca Salt.

163
00:18:06.336 --> 00:18:10.131
As soon as little Veruca told me she had
to have one of these golden tickets...

164
00:18:10.382 --> 00:18:13.385
...I started buying all the Wonka bars
I could lay my hands on.

165
00:18:14.010 --> 00:18:16.388
Thousands of them.
Hundreds of thousands.

166
00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:20.976
I'm in the nut business. you see.
So I say to my workers:

167
00:18:21.559 --> 00:18:24.521
Morning. ladies. From now on.
you can stop shelling peanuts...

168
00:18:24.688 --> 00:18:27.941
...and start shelling the wrappers
off these chocolate bars instead.

169
00:18:42.455 --> 00:18:44.374
<i>Three days went by.
and we had no luck.</i>

170
00:18:44.541 --> 00:18:48.086
<i>Oh. it was terrible. My Veruca
got more and more upset each day.</i>

171
00:18:48.253 --> 00:18:49.713
Where's my golden ticket?

172
00:18:49.879 --> 00:18:52.215
I want my golden ticket.

173
00:18:53.633 --> 00:18:57.387
Well. gentlemen. I just hated to see
my little girl feeling unhappy like that.

174
00:18:57.762 --> 00:19:01.099
I vowed I would keep searching
until I could give her what she wanted.

175
00:19:02.559 --> 00:19:05.895
<i>And finally. I found her a ticket.</i>

176
00:19:32.422 --> 00:19:35.717
Daddy. I want another pony.

177
00:19:37.635 --> 00:19:39.637
She's even worse than the fat boy.

178
00:19:40.180 --> 00:19:43.767
I don't think that was really fair.
She didn't find the ticket herself.

179
00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:48.396
Don't worry about it. Charlie.
That man spoils his daughter.

180
00:19:48.813 --> 00:19:52.484
And no good ever comes
from spoiling a child like that.

181
00:19:57.906 --> 00:20:01.201
Charlie. Mum and I thought...

182
00:20:01.368 --> 00:20:04.245
...maybe you wanna open
your birthday present tonight.

183
00:20:10.752 --> 00:20:12.128
Here you are.

184
00:20:24.557 --> 00:20:26.142
Maybe I should wait till morning.

185
00:20:26.393 --> 00:20:28.144
- Like hell.
- Pop.

186
00:20:28.645 --> 00:20:34.150
All together. we're 381 years old.
We don't wait.

187
00:20:42.158 --> 00:20:44.869
Now. Charlie.
you mustn't feel too disappointed...

188
00:20:45.036 --> 00:20:46.996
...you know. if you don't get the...

189
00:20:47.163 --> 00:20:49.332
Whatever happens.
you'll still have the candy.

190
00:21:18.862 --> 00:21:20.530
Ah. well.

191
00:21:20.989 --> 00:21:22.699
That's that.

192
00:21:24.492 --> 00:21:27.203
- We'll share it.
- Oh. no. Charlie.

193
00:21:27.370 --> 00:21:28.997
Not your birthday present.

194
00:21:29.873 --> 00:21:33.209
It's my candy bar.
and I'll do what I want with it.

195
00:21:39.883 --> 00:21:41.384
Thank you. darling.

196
00:21:42.343 --> 00:21:43.928
Thank you. Charlie.

197
00:21:48.391 --> 00:21:49.726
Bless you.

198
00:22:15.710 --> 00:22:17.837
All right. let's see who found it.

199
00:22:22.425 --> 00:22:25.762
"The third ticket was found
by Miss Violet Beauregarde."

200
00:22:25.929 --> 00:22:27.805
Hah! Hah! Hyah!

201
00:22:44.155 --> 00:22:50.078
These are just some of the 263
trophies and medals my Violet has won.

202
00:22:50.245 --> 00:22:53.665
I'm a gum chewer mostly. but when
I heard about these ticket things...

203
00:22:53.831 --> 00:22:56.042
...I laid off the gum.
switched to candy bars.

204
00:22:56.376 --> 00:22:59.420
She's just a driven young woman.
I don't know where she gets it.

205
00:23:02.006 --> 00:23:04.133
I'm the Junior World Champion
Gum Chewer.

206
00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:06.302
This piece of gum
I'm chewing right now...

207
00:23:06.469 --> 00:23:10.390
...I've been working on for
three months solid. That's a record.

208
00:23:10.557 --> 00:23:14.978
Of course. I did have my share
of trophies. mostly baton.

209
00:23:15.395 --> 00:23:19.607
So it says that one kid's gonna get
this special prize. better than all the rest.

210
00:23:20.149 --> 00:23:23.987
I don't care who those other four are.
That kid. it's gonna be me.

211
00:23:24.320 --> 00:23:25.613
Tell them why. Violet.

212
00:23:26.030 --> 00:23:27.365
<i>Because I'm a winner.</i>

213
00:23:27.907 --> 00:23:29.659
What a beastly girl.

214
00:23:29.826 --> 00:23:31.953
Despicable.

215
00:23:32.120 --> 00:23:34.330
You don't know
what we're talking about.

216
00:23:36.249 --> 00:23:38.001
Dragonflies?

217
00:23:38.167 --> 00:23:39.836
<i>But wait. this is just in.</i>

218
00:23:40.003 --> 00:23:45.508
<i>The fourth golden ticket has been found
by a boy called Mike Teavee.</i>

219
00:23:57.478 --> 00:24:00.273
All you had to do was track
the manufacturing dates...

220
00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:03.860
...offset by weather
and the derivative of the Nikkei Index.

221
00:24:04.319 --> 00:24:06.154
A retard could figure it out.

222
00:24:07.363 --> 00:24:10.033
Most of the time
I don't know what he's talking about.

223
00:24:10.199 --> 00:24:13.119
You know. kids these days.
what with all the technology...

224
00:24:13.286 --> 00:24:15.538
Die! Die! Die!

225
00:24:17.332 --> 00:24:19.542
Doesn't seem like
they stay kids very long.

226
00:24:24.631 --> 00:24:27.050
In the end.
I only had to buy one candy bar.

227
00:24:27.425 --> 00:24:30.219
- And how did it taste?
- I don't know.

228
00:24:30.386 --> 00:24:31.763
I hate chocolate.

229
00:24:31.929 --> 00:24:35.892
It's a good thing you're going to a
chocolate factory. you ungrateful little--

230
00:24:46.235 --> 00:24:49.614
<i>That question is.
who will be the winner of the last gold--?</i>

231
00:24:56.120 --> 00:24:57.747
- Dad?
- Yes. Charlie?

232
00:24:58.164 --> 00:24:59.999
Why aren't you at work?

233
00:25:01.167 --> 00:25:05.046
Oh. well. the toothpaste factory
thought they'd give me a bit of time off.

234
00:25:05.755 --> 00:25:07.090
Like summer vacation?

235
00:25:07.799 --> 00:25:10.134
Sure. Something like that.

236
00:25:13.554 --> 00:25:17.475
<i>In fact. it wasn't like a vacation at all.</i>

237
00:25:18.518 --> 00:25:22.772
<i>The upswing in candy sales
had led to a rise in cavities...</i>

238
00:25:22.939 --> 00:25:25.983
<i>...which led to a rise
in toothpaste sales.</i>

239
00:25:30.655 --> 00:25:34.450
<i>With the extra money.
the factory had decided to modernize...</i>

240
00:25:35.034 --> 00:25:38.579
<i>...eliminating Mr. Bucket's job.</i>

241
00:25:43.835 --> 00:25:46.462
We were barely making
ends meet as it was.

242
00:25:46.629 --> 00:25:48.673
You'll find another job.

243
00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:53.010
Until then. I'll just-- Well. I'll just
thin down the soup a little more.

244
00:25:54.470 --> 00:25:58.474
Don't worry. Mr. Bucket.
our luck will change.

245
00:25:58.808 --> 00:26:00.435
I know it.

246
00:26:04.147 --> 00:26:05.648
Charlie.

247
00:26:21.998 --> 00:26:24.167
My secret hoard.

248
00:26:27.170 --> 00:26:31.007
You and I are going to have
one more fling...

249
00:26:31.174 --> 00:26:33.468
...at finding that last ticket.

250
00:26:34.260 --> 00:26:36.471
You sure you want to spend
your money on that?

251
00:26:36.637 --> 00:26:39.348
Of course I'm sure. Here.

252
00:26:40.850 --> 00:26:43.102
Run down to the nearest store...

253
00:26:43.269 --> 00:26:47.106
...and buy the first
Wonka candy bar you see.

254
00:26:47.273 --> 00:26:50.818
Bring it straight back.
and we'll open it together.

255
00:26:59.202 --> 00:27:01.913
Such a good boy. really.

256
00:27:03.164 --> 00:27:04.373
Such a good...

257
00:27:06.918 --> 00:27:08.377
Grandpa?

258
00:27:09.420 --> 00:27:11.881
- You fell asleep.
- Have you got it?

259
00:27:17.386 --> 00:27:19.388
Which end should we open first?

260
00:27:19.764 --> 00:27:22.225
Just do it quick. like a Band-Aid.

261
00:27:52.463 --> 00:27:55.591
Did you see that some kid in Russia
found the last golden ticket?

262
00:27:55.758 --> 00:27:57.844
Yes. it was in the paper this morning.

263
00:27:58.010 --> 00:28:01.514
Good boy. Come on. George.
Good boy.

264
00:28:53.900 --> 00:28:56.652
One Wonka Whipple-Scrumptious
Fudgemallow Delight. please.

265
00:28:56.819 --> 00:28:59.322
Okay. Here you go.

266
00:29:04.994 --> 00:29:06.704
The nerve of some people.

267
00:29:07.330 --> 00:29:10.625
I know. Forging a ticket. Come on.

268
00:29:23.387 --> 00:29:25.640
It's a golden ticket.

269
00:29:27.391 --> 00:29:30.978
You found Wonka's last golden ticket.

270
00:29:31.562 --> 00:29:33.648
In my shop too!

271
00:29:34.190 --> 00:29:38.194
Listen. I'll buy it from you.
I'll give you $50 and a new bicycle.

272
00:29:38.361 --> 00:29:41.489
Are you crazy?
I'd give him $500 for that ticket.

273
00:29:41.656 --> 00:29:44.200
You wanna sell me your ticket
for $500. young man?

274
00:29:44.367 --> 00:29:46.661
That's enough of that.
Leave the kid alone.

275
00:29:47.286 --> 00:29:52.375
Listen. Don't let anyone have it.
Take it straight home. you understand?

276
00:29:53.876 --> 00:29:55.211
Thank you.

277
00:30:02.510 --> 00:30:04.679
Mom! Dad!

278
00:30:05.554 --> 00:30:07.723
I found it!

279
00:30:07.890 --> 00:30:10.393
The last golden ticket! It's mine!

280
00:30:24.407 --> 00:30:25.908
Yippee!

281
00:30:32.873 --> 00:30:34.083
Here.

282
00:30:34.917 --> 00:30:38.045
Read it aloud.
Let's hear exactly what it says.

283
00:30:39.046 --> 00:30:44.010
"Greetings to you. the lucky finder of
this golden ticket. from Mr. Willy Wonka.

284
00:30:44.510 --> 00:30:48.639
I shake you warmly by the hand.
For now. I invite you to my factory...

285
00:30:48.806 --> 00:30:52.018
...and be my guest
for one whole day."

286
00:30:52.184 --> 00:30:55.438
"L. Willy Wonka. will conduct you
around the factory myself...

287
00:30:55.604 --> 00:30:57.606
...showing you everything
there is to see."

288
00:30:57.815 --> 00:30:59.775
"Afterwards.
when it is time to leave...

289
00:30:59.942 --> 00:31:03.320
...you will be escorted home
by a procession of large trucks...

290
00:31:03.487 --> 00:31:06.782
...each one filled with all the chocolate
you could ever eat."

291
00:31:06.949 --> 00:31:11.662
"And remember. one of you lucky
five children will receive an extra prize...

292
00:31:11.829 --> 00:31:14.040
...beyond your wildest imagination.

293
00:31:14.206 --> 00:31:16.584
Now. here are your instructions."

294
00:31:16.751 --> 00:31:20.671
"On the 1st of February. you must come
to the factory gates at 10 a.m. sharp.

295
00:31:20.838 --> 00:31:24.216
You're allowed to bring one member
of your family to look after you.

296
00:31:24.383 --> 00:31:26.427
Until then. Willy Wonka."

297
00:31:27.303 --> 00:31:28.637
The 1st of February.

298
00:31:29.722 --> 00:31:32.600
- But that's tomorrow.
- Then there's not a moment to lose.

299
00:31:32.767 --> 00:31:34.935
Wash your face. comb your hair.
scrub your hands...

300
00:31:35.102 --> 00:31:36.604
...brush your teeth. blow your nose.

301
00:31:36.771 --> 00:31:38.064
And get that mud off your pants.

302
00:31:38.272 --> 00:31:40.274
We must all try and keep very calm.

303
00:31:40.816 --> 00:31:45.154
First thing that we have to decide is this:
Who is going with Charlie to the factory?

304
00:31:45.446 --> 00:31:48.574
I will. I'll take him. You leave it to me.

305
00:31:48.949 --> 00:31:51.452
How about you. dear?
Don't you think you ought to go?

306
00:31:51.827 --> 00:31:56.165
Well. Grandpa Joe seems to know
more about it than we do. and...

307
00:31:57.124 --> 00:31:59.168
Provided. of course.
he feels well enough.

308
00:31:59.376 --> 00:32:01.921
Yippee!

309
00:32:02.588 --> 00:32:05.174
No. We're not going.

310
00:32:08.511 --> 00:32:11.764
A woman offered me $500
for the ticket.

311
00:32:11.931 --> 00:32:14.016
I bet someone else would pay more.

312
00:32:14.183 --> 00:32:16.560
We need the money more
than we need the chocolate.

313
00:32:26.654 --> 00:32:29.031
Young man. come here.

314
00:32:32.868 --> 00:32:35.538
There's plenty of money out there.

315
00:32:35.704 --> 00:32:37.832
They print more every day.

316
00:32:38.791 --> 00:32:40.709
But this ticket...

317
00:32:40.876 --> 00:32:44.797
...there's only five of them
in the whole world...

318
00:32:44.964 --> 00:32:47.299
...and that's all
there's ever going to be.

319
00:32:48.134 --> 00:32:53.222
Only a dummy would give this up
for something as common as money.

320
00:32:53.764 --> 00:32:55.975
Are you a dummy?

321
00:32:56.892 --> 00:32:58.227
No. sir.

322
00:32:58.894 --> 00:33:02.857
Then get that mud off your pants.
You've got a factory to go to.

323
00:33:46.942 --> 00:33:49.278
Daddy. I want to go in.

324
00:33:49.445 --> 00:33:50.946
It's 9:59. sweetheart.

325
00:33:51.113 --> 00:33:53.657
Make time go faster.

326
00:33:54.033 --> 00:33:56.035
Do you think Mr. Wonka
will recognize you?

327
00:33:56.202 --> 00:34:00.164
Hard to say. It's been years.

328
00:34:07.588 --> 00:34:09.298
Eyes on the prize. Violet.

329
00:34:09.465 --> 00:34:11.759
Eyes on the prize.

330
00:34:29.443 --> 00:34:32.029
<i>Please enter.</i>

331
00:34:43.457 --> 00:34:46.460
<i>Come forward.</i>

332
00:34:50.339 --> 00:34:53.592
<i>Close the gates.</i>

333
00:35:01.809 --> 00:35:03.852
<i>Dear visitors...</i>

334
00:35:04.019 --> 00:35:09.233
<i>...it is my great pleasure to welcome you
to my humble factory.</i>

335
00:35:11.568 --> 00:35:13.570
<i>And who am I?</i>

336
00:35:14.989 --> 00:35:16.740
<i>Well...</i>

337
00:35:20.244 --> 00:35:22.246
<i>Willy Wonka. Willy Wonka</i>

338
00:35:22.413 --> 00:35:24.373
<i>The amazing chocolatier</i>

339
00:35:24.540 --> 00:35:26.542
<i>Willy Wonka. Willy Wonka</i>

340
00:35:26.709 --> 00:35:28.669
<i>Everybody give a cheer!
Hooray!</i>

341
00:35:28.836 --> 00:35:30.713
<i>He's modest. clever and so smart</i>

342
00:35:30.879 --> 00:35:32.548
<i>He barely can restrain it</i>

343
00:35:32.715 --> 00:35:34.717
<i>With so much generosity</i>

344
00:35:34.883 --> 00:35:36.552
<i>There is no way to contain it!</i>

345
00:35:36.719 --> 00:35:40.097
<i>To contain it
To contain. to contain. to contain!</i>

346
00:35:40.556 --> 00:35:42.099
<i>Hooray!</i>

347
00:35:42.683 --> 00:35:44.601
<i>Willy Wonka. Willy Wonka</i>

348
00:35:44.768 --> 00:35:46.603
<i>He's the one that you're about to meet</i>

349
00:35:46.770 --> 00:35:48.355
<i>Willy Wonka. Willy Wonka</i>

350
00:35:48.522 --> 00:35:50.816
<i>He's the genius who just can't be beat</i>

351
00:35:50.983 --> 00:35:52.735
<i>The magician and the chocolate wiz</i>

352
00:35:52.943 --> 00:35:54.611
<i>The best darn guy who ever lived</i>

353
00:35:54.778 --> 00:36:00.409
<i>Willy Wonka. here he is!</i>

354
00:36:18.969 --> 00:36:21.847
<i>The amazing chocolatier</i>

355
00:36:32.107 --> 00:36:34.068
Wasn't that just magnificent?

356
00:36:34.234 --> 00:36:38.906
I was worried it was getting dodgy
in the middle part. but then that finale...

357
00:36:39.073 --> 00:36:40.949
Wow!

358
00:36:43.285 --> 00:36:45.079
Who are you?

359
00:36:45.788 --> 00:36:48.791
- He's Willy Wonka.
- Really?

360
00:36:58.801 --> 00:37:00.969
"Good morning. star shine.

361
00:37:01.136 --> 00:37:03.305
The Earth says hello."

362
00:37:11.480 --> 00:37:13.524
"Dear guests. greetings.

363
00:37:14.733 --> 00:37:18.612
Welcome to the factory.
I shake you warmly by the hand.

364
00:37:22.199 --> 00:37:25.077
My name is Willy Wonka."

365
00:37:25.244 --> 00:37:26.954
Then shouldn't you be up there?

366
00:37:27.788 --> 00:37:31.458
I couldn't very well watch the show
from up there. now. could I. little girl?

367
00:37:31.625 --> 00:37:35.462
Mr. Wonka. I don't know
if you'll remember me...

368
00:37:35.629 --> 00:37:38.507
...but I used to work
here in the factory.

369
00:37:39.007 --> 00:37:42.010
Were you one of those despicable spies
who tried to steal...

370
00:37:42.177 --> 00:37:46.056
...my life's work and sell it to parasitic.
copycat. candy-making cads?

371
00:37:46.348 --> 00:37:47.558
No. sir.

372
00:37:48.225 --> 00:37:49.810
Then wonderful. Welcome back.

373
00:37:49.977 --> 00:37:51.353
Let's get a move on. kids.

374
00:37:54.440 --> 00:37:56.817
Don't you want to know our names?

375
00:37:56.984 --> 00:38:01.697
Can't imagine how it would matter.
Come quickly. Far too much to see.

376
00:38:07.369 --> 00:38:09.204
Just drop your coats anywhere.

377
00:38:15.377 --> 00:38:18.714
- Mr. Wonka? Sure is toasty in here.
- What?

378
00:38:19.339 --> 00:38:24.011
Oh. I have to keep it warm. My workers
are used to an extremely hot climate.

379
00:38:24.178 --> 00:38:26.388
They just can't stand the cold.

380
00:38:26.555 --> 00:38:27.764
Who are the workers?

381
00:38:28.348 --> 00:38:30.184
All in good time. Now...

382
00:38:34.980 --> 00:38:36.565
Mr. Wonka. I'm Violet Beauregarde.

383
00:38:37.608 --> 00:38:39.318
Oh.

384
00:38:39.526 --> 00:38:41.570
- I don't care.
- Well. you should care.

385
00:38:41.737 --> 00:38:44.198
Because I'm gonna win
the special prize at the end.

386
00:38:44.364 --> 00:38:47.284
Well. you do seem confident.
and confidence is key.

387
00:38:50.329 --> 00:38:53.415
I'm Veruca Salt.
It's very nice to meet you. sir.

388
00:38:53.916 --> 00:38:56.251
I always thought a verruca
was a type of wart you got...

389
00:38:56.460 --> 00:38:57.920
...on the bottom of your foot.

390
00:39:00.422 --> 00:39:03.383
I am Augustus Gloop.
I love your chocolate.

391
00:39:04.593 --> 00:39:07.262
I can see that. So do I.

392
00:39:07.429 --> 00:39:10.557
I never expected to have
so much in common.

393
00:39:14.603 --> 00:39:17.397
You. You're Mike Teavee.

394
00:39:17.898 --> 00:39:20.108
You're the little devil
who cracked the system.

395
00:39:22.319 --> 00:39:25.280
And you. Well. you're just lucky
to be here. aren't you?

396
00:39:27.407 --> 00:39:29.952
And the rest of you must be their--

397
00:39:37.417 --> 00:39:39.836
- Parents.
- Yeah.

398
00:39:40.003 --> 00:39:42.005
Moms and dads.

399
00:39:43.674 --> 00:39:45.217
Dad?

400
00:39:47.177 --> 00:39:49.096
Papa?

401
00:39:55.561 --> 00:39:58.272
Okay. then. Let's move along.

402
00:40:06.947 --> 00:40:10.993
Is it just me or does Wonka seem
a few quarters short of a buck?

403
00:40:11.159 --> 00:40:13.328
I'm sorry. I don't speak American.

404
00:40:15.038 --> 00:40:17.207
- Would you like some chocolate?
- Sure.

405
00:40:17.374 --> 00:40:19.501
Then you should've brought some.

406
00:40:23.171 --> 00:40:25.549
- Let's be friends.
- Best friends.

407
00:40:37.936 --> 00:40:39.688
An important room. this.

408
00:40:39.855 --> 00:40:43.692
- After all. it is a chocolate factory.
- Then why is the door so small?

409
00:40:44.401 --> 00:40:46.987
That's to keep all the great big
chocolatey flavor inside.

410
00:41:09.843 --> 00:41:13.055
Now. do be careful. my dear children.

411
00:41:13.221 --> 00:41:15.015
Don't lose your heads.

412
00:41:15.182 --> 00:41:17.059
Don't get overexcited.

413
00:41:18.018 --> 00:41:21.104
Just keep very calm.

414
00:41:36.870 --> 00:41:38.080
It's beautiful.

415
00:41:39.081 --> 00:41:40.791
What?

416
00:41:41.208 --> 00:41:43.251
Oh. yeah. it's very beautiful.

417
00:41:53.095 --> 00:41:55.430
Every drop of the river...

418
00:41:55.597 --> 00:41:59.101
...is hot. melted chocolate
of the finest quality.

419
00:42:04.272 --> 00:42:06.566
The waterfall is most important.

420
00:42:06.733 --> 00:42:08.443
Mixes the chocolate.

421
00:42:08.610 --> 00:42:11.613
Churns it up. Makes it light and frothy.

422
00:42:12.197 --> 00:42:13.448
By the way...

423
00:42:13.615 --> 00:42:19.371
...no other factory in the world mixes its
chocolate by waterfall. my dear children.

424
00:42:19.538 --> 00:42:21.415
And you can take that to the bank.

425
00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:33.385
People.

426
00:42:35.554 --> 00:42:37.472
Those pipes...

427
00:42:37.973 --> 00:42:42.602
...suck up the chocolate
and carry it away all over the factory.

428
00:42:43.311 --> 00:42:45.981
Thousands of gallons an hour. Yeah.

429
00:42:47.399 --> 00:42:50.318
And do you like my meadow?
Try some of my grass.

430
00:42:50.485 --> 00:42:55.031
Please have a blade. Please do. It's
so delectable and so darn good-looking.

431
00:42:55.699 --> 00:42:57.159
You can eat the grass?

432
00:42:57.325 --> 00:42:59.411
Of course you can.

433
00:42:59.578 --> 00:43:01.830
Everything in this room is eatable.

434
00:43:01.997 --> 00:43:03.331
Even I'm eatable.

435
00:43:03.498 --> 00:43:06.334
But that is called cannibalism.
my dear children...

436
00:43:06.501 --> 00:43:09.337
...and is. in fact. frowned upon
in most societies.

437
00:43:09.588 --> 00:43:10.839
Yeah.

438
00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:13.425
Enjoy.

439
00:43:14.092 --> 00:43:16.344
Go on. Scoot. scoot.

440
00:43:37.616 --> 00:43:39.075
Son.

441
00:43:40.494 --> 00:43:41.703
Please.

442
00:43:42.829 --> 00:43:45.540
Dad. he said. "Enjoy."

443
00:43:59.429 --> 00:44:02.432
Why hold on to it?
Why not start a new piece?

444
00:44:03.225 --> 00:44:07.729
Because then I wouldn't be a champion.
I'd be a loser. like you.

445
00:44:36.716 --> 00:44:38.385
Daddy. look over there.

446
00:44:40.053 --> 00:44:41.763
What is it?

447
00:44:41.930 --> 00:44:43.473
It's a little person.

448
00:44:43.640 --> 00:44:46.101
Over there. by the waterfall.

449
00:44:48.270 --> 00:44:50.939
- There's two of them.
- There's more than two.

450
00:44:57.279 --> 00:44:59.906
- Where do they come from?
- Who are they?

451
00:45:01.658 --> 00:45:03.451
Are they real people?

452
00:45:03.618 --> 00:45:06.121
Of course they're real people.
They're Oompa-Loompas.

453
00:45:09.833 --> 00:45:12.794
- Oompa-Loompas?
- Imported. direct from Loompaland.

454
00:45:12.961 --> 00:45:15.589
- There's no such place.
- What?

455
00:45:15.755 --> 00:45:19.259
Mr. Wonka. I teach high-school
geography. and I'm here to tell you--

456
00:45:19.426 --> 00:45:24.598
Well. then you'll know all about it.
and. oh. what a terrible country it is.

457
00:45:35.609 --> 00:45:37.944
<i>The whole place is nothing
but thick jungles...</i>

458
00:45:38.111 --> 00:45:41.698
<i>...infested by the most dangerous beasts
in the entire world.</i>

459
00:45:42.532 --> 00:45:46.995
<i>Hornswogglers and snozzwangers and
those terrible. wicked whangdoodles.</i>

460
00:46:08.141 --> 00:46:12.062
<i>I went to Loompaland looking for
exotic new flavors for candy.</i>

461
00:46:16.149 --> 00:46:17.442
<i>Instead...</i>

462
00:46:17.609 --> 00:46:19.653
<i>...I found the Oompa-Loompas.</i>

463
00:46:27.786 --> 00:46:32.749
<i>They lived in tree houses to escape from
the fierce creatures who lived below.</i>

464
00:46:36.294 --> 00:46:40.548
<i>The Oompa-Loompas ate nothing but
green caterpillars. which tasted revolting.</i>

465
00:46:41.883 --> 00:46:43.718
<i>The Oompa-Loompas looked for things...</i>

466
00:46:43.885 --> 00:46:46.846
<i>...to mash up with the caterpillars
to make them taste better:</i>

467
00:46:47.097 --> 00:46:50.517
<i>Red beetles.
the bark of the bong-bong tree.</i>

468
00:46:50.684 --> 00:46:51.935
<i>All of them beastly...</i>

469
00:46:52.477 --> 00:46:55.105
<i>...but not quite so beastly
as the caterpillars.</i>

470
00:47:01.861 --> 00:47:03.655
Mmm.

471
00:47:27.387 --> 00:47:31.474
<i>But the food they longed for the most
was the cocoa bean.</i>

472
00:47:35.311 --> 00:47:39.024
<i>An Oompa-Loompa was lucky if he found
three or four cocoa beans a year.</i>

473
00:47:39.190 --> 00:47:41.609
<i>But. oh. how they craved them.</i>

474
00:47:42.819 --> 00:47:45.947
<i>All they'd ever think about
was cocoa beans.</i>

475
00:47:51.327 --> 00:47:55.623
The cocoa bean is the thing from which
chocolate is made. so I told the chief:

476
00:48:16.311 --> 00:48:18.980
They are such wonderful workers.

477
00:48:19.147 --> 00:48:22.108
I feel I must warn you. though.
they are rather mischievous.

478
00:48:22.275 --> 00:48:24.069
Always making jokes.

479
00:48:24.694 --> 00:48:27.989
Augustus. my child.
that is not a good thing you do!

480
00:48:30.492 --> 00:48:31.993
Hey. little boy.

481
00:48:32.160 --> 00:48:35.205
My chocolate must be untouched
by human hands.

482
00:48:36.164 --> 00:48:37.457
Ah!

483
00:48:42.170 --> 00:48:43.671
He'll drown.

484
00:48:45.090 --> 00:48:46.633
He can't swim.

485
00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:48.343
Save him!

486
00:48:49.552 --> 00:48:52.347
Augustus! No!

487
00:48:58.686 --> 00:49:00.730
Augustus!

488
00:49:09.739 --> 00:49:12.700
Augustus. watch out!

489
00:49:12.909 --> 00:49:14.661
Ah!

490
00:49:14.828 --> 00:49:16.704
Ah!

491
00:49:29.217 --> 00:49:30.802
There he goes.

492
00:49:31.219 --> 00:49:34.055
- Ah!
- Call the fire brigade!

493
00:49:34.222 --> 00:49:36.516
It's a wonder how
that pipe is big enough.

494
00:49:37.392 --> 00:49:39.561
It isn't big enough.
He's slowing down.

495
00:49:39.727 --> 00:49:41.020
He's gonna stick.

496
00:49:42.605 --> 00:49:43.898
I think he has.

497
00:49:47.443 --> 00:49:48.945
He's blocked the whole pipe.

498
00:49:51.990 --> 00:49:53.950
Look. The Oompa-Loompas.

499
00:49:57.954 --> 00:49:59.414
Back off. you little freaks!

500
00:50:02.333 --> 00:50:03.918
What are they doing?

501
00:50:06.296 --> 00:50:10.175
They're going to treat us to a little song.
It is quite a special occasion.

502
00:50:10.341 --> 00:50:12.677
They haven't had a fresh audience
in many a moon.

503
00:50:32.614 --> 00:50:35.116
<i>Augustus Gloop. Augustus Gloop</i>

504
00:50:35.700 --> 00:50:38.036
<i>The great big. greedy nincompoop</i>

505
00:50:38.203 --> 00:50:43.082
<i>Augustus Gloop. so big and vile
So greedy. foul and infantile</i>

506
00:50:43.249 --> 00:50:45.585
<i>"Come on!" we cried
"The time is ripe</i>

507
00:50:45.752 --> 00:50:48.296
<i>To send him shooting up the pipe!"</i>

508
00:50:48.463 --> 00:50:50.757
<i>But don't. dear children. be alarmed</i>

509
00:50:51.049 --> 00:50:53.551
<i>Augustus Gloop will not be harmed</i>

510
00:50:53.718 --> 00:50:55.970
<i>Augustus Gloop will not be harmed</i>

511
00:51:27.460 --> 00:51:29.462
<i>Although. of course. we must admit</i>

512
00:51:29.671 --> 00:51:31.839
<i>He will be altered quite a bit</i>

513
00:51:32.465 --> 00:51:34.968
<i>Slowly. wheels go round and round</i>

514
00:51:35.176 --> 00:51:37.178
<i>And cogs begin to grind and pound</i>

515
00:51:37.345 --> 00:51:39.973
<i>We'll boil him for a minute more</i>

516
00:51:40.139 --> 00:51:42.350
<i>Until we're absolutely sure</i>

517
00:51:42.517 --> 00:51:45.186
<i>Then out he comes. by God. by grace</i>

518
00:51:45.353 --> 00:51:47.730
<i>A miracle has taken place</i>

519
00:51:47.897 --> 00:51:50.358
<i>A miracle has taken place</i>

520
00:51:50.525 --> 00:51:53.236
<i>This greedy brute. this louse's ear</i>

521
00:51:55.697 --> 00:51:57.865
<i>Is loved by people everywhere</i>

522
00:51:58.032 --> 00:52:00.868
<i>For who could hate or bear a grudge</i>

523
00:52:01.035 --> 00:52:07.083
<i>Against a luscious bit of fudge?</i>

524
00:52:14.966 --> 00:52:16.884
Ah!

525
00:52:33.234 --> 00:52:35.194
Bravo! Well done!

526
00:52:35.403 --> 00:52:37.572
Aren't they delightful?
Aren't they charming?

527
00:52:37.739 --> 00:52:42.243
- I say. that all seemed rather rehearsed.
- Like they knew it was gonna happen.

528
00:52:42.952 --> 00:52:44.704
Oh. poppycock.

529
00:52:47.915 --> 00:52:50.543
Where is my son?
Where does that pipe go to?

530
00:52:52.211 --> 00:52:54.505
That pipe. it just so happens to lead...

531
00:52:54.672 --> 00:52:57.008
...directly to the room
where I make delicious...

532
00:52:57.175 --> 00:52:59.594
...strawberry-flavored.
chocolate-coated fudge.

533
00:52:59.761 --> 00:53:03.306
He will be made into strawberry-flavored.
chocolate-coated fudge.

534
00:53:03.473 --> 00:53:07.018
They'll be selling him by the pound
all over the world?

535
00:53:07.185 --> 00:53:10.063
No. I wouldn't allow it.
The taste would be terrible.

536
00:53:10.646 --> 00:53:14.400
Can you imagine Augustus-flavored.
chocolate-coated Gloop? Ew.

537
00:53:14.567 --> 00:53:15.943
No one would buy it.

538
00:53:24.744 --> 00:53:28.039
I want you to take Mrs. Gloop
up to the Fudge Room. okay?

539
00:53:28.206 --> 00:53:29.707
Help her find her son.

540
00:53:29.874 --> 00:53:35.463
Take a long stick and start poking around
in the big chocolate-mixing barrel. okay?

541
00:53:52.230 --> 00:53:53.815
- Mr. Wonka?
- Huh?

542
00:53:54.148 --> 00:53:57.693
Why would Augustus' name already
be in the Oompa-Loompa song. unless--?

543
00:53:57.860 --> 00:54:01.489
Improvisation is a parlor trick.
Anyone can do it.

544
00:54:02.073 --> 00:54:03.783
You. little girl. Say something.

545
00:54:03.991 --> 00:54:05.993
- Anything.
- Chewing gum.

546
00:54:07.036 --> 00:54:09.205
<i>Chewing gum is really gross
Chewing gum. I hate the most</i>

547
00:54:09.372 --> 00:54:11.416
See? Exactly the same.

548
00:54:11.582 --> 00:54:13.000
No. it isn't.

549
00:54:13.584 --> 00:54:15.670
Uh. you really shouldn't mumble.

550
00:54:15.837 --> 00:54:18.131
Because I can't understand
a word you're saying.

551
00:54:20.341 --> 00:54:23.136
Now. on with the tour.

552
00:54:25.888 --> 00:54:29.809
- Are the Oompa-Loompas really joking?
- Of course they're joking.

553
00:54:30.017 --> 00:54:32.520
That boy will be fine.

554
00:55:21.444 --> 00:55:22.695
What's so funny?

555
00:55:23.446 --> 00:55:26.199
I think it's from all those
doggone cocoa beans.

556
00:55:26.365 --> 00:55:30.244
Hey. by the way. did you guys know
that chocolate contains a property...

557
00:55:30.411 --> 00:55:35.208
...that triggers the release of endorphins?
Gives one the feeling of being in love.

558
00:55:35.583 --> 00:55:37.084
You don't say.

559
00:55:39.962 --> 00:55:41.881
All aboard.

560
00:55:52.391 --> 00:55:53.601
Onward!

561
00:56:17.625 --> 00:56:19.126
Here.

562
00:56:19.293 --> 00:56:23.839
Try some of this. It'll do you good.
You look starved to death.

563
00:56:25.341 --> 00:56:29.762
- It's great.
- That's because it's mixed by waterfall.

564
00:56:29.929 --> 00:56:31.472
The waterfall is most important.

565
00:56:31.639 --> 00:56:35.893
Mixes the chocolate. churns it up.
makes it light and frothy.

566
00:56:36.477 --> 00:56:40.565
- No other factory in the world--
- You already said that.

567
00:56:46.153 --> 00:56:49.782
- You're all quite short. aren't you?
- Well. yeah. We're children.

568
00:56:49.949 --> 00:56:52.577
Well. that's no excuse.
I was never as short as you.

569
00:56:52.743 --> 00:56:56.038
- You were once.
- Was not. Know why?

570
00:56:56.205 --> 00:56:59.917
Because I distinctly remember
putting a hat on top of my head.

571
00:57:00.084 --> 00:57:03.713
Look at your short. little arms.
You could never reach.

572
00:57:06.382 --> 00:57:08.718
Do you even remember
what it was like being a kid?

573
00:57:08.884 --> 00:57:10.970
Oh. boy. do I.

574
00:57:14.557 --> 00:57:15.808
Do I?

575
00:57:15.975 --> 00:57:17.393
<i>In fact. Willy Wonka...</i>

576
00:57:17.560 --> 00:57:20.896
<i>...hadn't thought about his childhood
for years.</i>

577
00:57:21.063 --> 00:57:23.482
Trick or treat!

578
00:57:23.816 --> 00:57:25.401
Trick or treat!

579
00:57:33.492 --> 00:57:35.036
Trick or treat!

580
00:57:37.121 --> 00:57:38.539
Who do we have here?

581
00:57:38.706 --> 00:57:42.418
Ruthie. Veronica. Terrance.

582
00:57:42.585 --> 00:57:44.128
And who's that under the sheet?

583
00:57:46.339 --> 00:57:49.383
Little Willy Wonka.

584
00:57:52.219 --> 00:57:56.682
<i>Willy Wonka was the son
of the city's most famous dentist...</i>

585
00:57:56.849 --> 00:57:58.809
<i>...Wilbur Wonka.</i>

586
00:58:05.733 --> 00:58:07.360
Now...

587
00:58:07.526 --> 00:58:10.363
...let's see what the damage is
this year. shall we?

588
00:58:24.502 --> 00:58:26.337
Caramels.

589
00:58:26.879 --> 00:58:30.174
They'd get stuck in your braces.
wouldn't they?

590
00:58:34.595 --> 00:58:36.972
Lollipops.

591
00:58:37.139 --> 00:58:40.893
Ought to be called
"cavities on a stick."

592
00:58:41.769 --> 00:58:43.521
Then we have all this...

593
00:58:43.688 --> 00:58:45.064
All this...

594
00:58:45.523 --> 00:58:47.066
...chocolate.

595
00:58:49.068 --> 00:58:53.072
You know. just last week. I was reading
in a very important medical journal...

596
00:58:53.280 --> 00:58:57.910
...that some children
are allergic to chocolate.

597
00:58:58.077 --> 00:59:00.788
Makes their noses itch.

598
00:59:01.163 --> 00:59:03.416
Maybe I'm not allergic.

599
00:59:03.582 --> 00:59:05.918
- I could try a piece.
- Really?

600
00:59:07.169 --> 00:59:09.213
But why take a chance?

601
00:59:24.729 --> 00:59:27.565
Mr. Wonka? Mr. Wonka?

602
00:59:27.732 --> 00:59:30.067
- We're headed for a tunnel.
- Oh. yeah.

603
00:59:30.443 --> 00:59:31.652
Full speed ahead.

604
00:59:38.451 --> 00:59:41.328
- How can they see where they're going?
- They can't.

605
00:59:41.829 --> 00:59:43.831
There's no knowing
where they're going.

606
00:59:44.206 --> 00:59:45.458
Switch on the lights!

607
01:00:13.068 --> 01:00:14.612
People. keep an eye out.

608
01:00:14.779 --> 01:00:16.906
We're passing some
very important rooms here.

609
01:00:22.495 --> 01:00:24.038
What do you use hair cream for?

610
01:00:25.206 --> 01:00:26.874
To lock in moisture.

611
01:00:34.048 --> 01:00:36.550
- Whipped cream.
- Precisely.

612
01:00:37.301 --> 01:00:38.469
That doesn't make sense.

613
01:00:39.637 --> 01:00:41.347
For your information. little girl...

614
01:00:41.514 --> 01:00:45.351
...whipped cream isn't whipped cream at
all unless it's been whipped with whips.

615
01:00:45.518 --> 01:00:47.645
Everybody knows that.

616
01:01:37.236 --> 01:01:40.197
Stop the boat.
I wanna show you guys something.

617
01:02:00.968 --> 01:02:04.221
Now. this is the most important room
in the entire factory.

618
01:02:04.680 --> 01:02:08.851
Now. everyone. enjoy yourselves.
but just don't touch anything.

619
01:02:09.018 --> 01:02:10.269
Okay? Go on.

620
01:02:10.477 --> 01:02:11.770
Go on. scoot.

621
01:02:23.282 --> 01:02:25.117
Hey. Mr. Wonka. what's this?

622
01:02:26.118 --> 01:02:29.288
Oh. Let me show you.

623
01:02:31.123 --> 01:02:32.374
Thank you.

624
01:02:32.541 --> 01:02:34.710
These are Everlasting Gobstoppers.

625
01:02:34.877 --> 01:02:37.588
They're for children who are given
very little allowance.

626
01:02:37.755 --> 01:02:41.175
You can suck on it all year.
and it'll never get any smaller.

627
01:02:41.508 --> 01:02:43.802
- Isn't that neat?
- It's like gum.

628
01:02:44.386 --> 01:02:46.889
No. Gum is for chewing.

629
01:02:47.056 --> 01:02:49.350
If you tried chewing
one of these Gobstoppers...

630
01:02:49.516 --> 01:02:51.560
...you'd break all your little teeth off.

631
01:02:51.727 --> 01:02:54.063
But they sure do taste terrific.

632
01:03:01.278 --> 01:03:03.739
And this is Hair Toffee.

633
01:03:03.906 --> 01:03:06.241
You suck down one of
these little boogers...

634
01:03:06.408 --> 01:03:08.327
...and in exactly half an hour...

635
01:03:08.535 --> 01:03:12.247
...a brand-new crop of hair will grow out
over the top of your little noggin.

636
01:03:12.414 --> 01:03:14.625
And a mustache. And a beard.

637
01:03:14.792 --> 01:03:17.336
- Who wants a beard?
- Well...

638
01:03:17.544 --> 01:03:20.673
...beatniks. for one.
Folk singers and motorbike riders.

639
01:03:20.839 --> 01:03:24.969
You know. all those hip. jazzy.
super-cool. neat. keen and groovy cats.

640
01:03:25.135 --> 01:03:27.638
It's in the fridge. daddy-o.
Are you hep to the jive?

641
01:03:27.805 --> 01:03:29.890
Can you dig what I'm laying down?
I knew you could.

642
01:03:30.057 --> 01:03:32.685
Slide me some skin. soul brother.

643
01:03:35.896 --> 01:03:37.898
Unfortunately.
the mixture isn't right yet.

644
01:03:38.065 --> 01:03:41.360
Because an Oompa-Loompa
tried some yesterday. and. well. he--

645
01:03:46.198 --> 01:03:47.366
How are you today?

646
01:03:49.159 --> 01:03:50.577
You look great.

647
01:03:59.253 --> 01:04:00.713
Watch this.

648
01:04:29.199 --> 01:04:30.451
You mean that's it?

649
01:04:30.951 --> 01:04:32.870
Do you even know what "it" is?

650
01:04:33.245 --> 01:04:35.247
- It's gum.
- Yeah.

651
01:04:35.414 --> 01:04:39.418
It's a stick of the most amazing and
sensational gum in the whole universe.

652
01:04:39.626 --> 01:04:41.754
Know why? Know why?

653
01:04:41.920 --> 01:04:45.174
Because this gum is a full
three-course dinner all by itself.

654
01:04:48.469 --> 01:04:49.928
Why would anyone want that?

655
01:04:57.311 --> 01:04:59.813
"It will be the end of all kitchens
and all cooking.

656
01:04:59.980 --> 01:05:03.692
Just a little strip of Wonka's magic
chewing gum and that is all you will...

657
01:05:03.859 --> 01:05:05.986
...ever need at breakfast.
lunch and dinner.

658
01:05:06.153 --> 01:05:10.574
This piece of gum happens to be tomato
soup. roast beef and blueberry pie."

659
01:05:10.741 --> 01:05:12.659
It sounds great.

660
01:05:13.160 --> 01:05:16.288
- It sounds weird.
- It sounds like my kind of gum.

661
01:05:19.166 --> 01:05:22.086
I'd rather you didn't.
There are still some things that are--

662
01:05:22.252 --> 01:05:25.672
I'm the world-record holder in
chewing gum. I'm not afraid of anything.

663
01:05:31.261 --> 01:05:34.348
- How is it. honey?
- It's amazing!

664
01:05:34.515 --> 01:05:37.142
Tomato soup.
I can feel it running down my throat.

665
01:05:37.309 --> 01:05:38.769
Yeah. Spit it out.

666
01:05:38.936 --> 01:05:41.480
- Young lady. I think you'd better--
- It's changing.

667
01:05:42.231 --> 01:05:44.483
Roast beef. with baked potato.

668
01:05:44.817 --> 01:05:47.486
- Crispy skin and butter.
- Keep chewing.

669
01:05:47.694 --> 01:05:50.989
My little girl's gonna be the first person
to have a chewing-gum meal.

670
01:05:51.198 --> 01:05:53.617
Yeah. I'm just a little concerned
about the--

671
01:05:53.784 --> 01:05:55.452
Blueberry pie and ice cream!

672
01:05:56.036 --> 01:05:58.539
- That part.
- What's happening to her nose?

673
01:06:04.211 --> 01:06:05.504
It's turning blue.

674
01:06:08.382 --> 01:06:10.134
Your whole nose has gone purple.

675
01:06:10.717 --> 01:06:12.719
What do you mean?

676
01:06:13.345 --> 01:06:16.056
Violet. you're turning violet.

677
01:06:17.099 --> 01:06:20.686
- What's happening?
- I told you I hadn't quite got it right.

678
01:06:20.853 --> 01:06:23.897
Because it goes a little funny
when it gets to the dessert.

679
01:06:24.064 --> 01:06:25.774
It's the blueberry pie that does it.

680
01:06:26.567 --> 01:06:28.735
I'm terribly sorry.

681
01:06:37.369 --> 01:06:40.747
Mother? What's happening to me?

682
01:06:53.468 --> 01:06:54.887
She's swelling up.

683
01:06:59.016 --> 01:07:00.267
Like a blueberry.

684
01:07:29.004 --> 01:07:33.050
I've tried it on. like. 20 Oompa-Loompas.
and each one ended up as a blueberry.

685
01:07:33.217 --> 01:07:35.010
It's just weird.

686
01:07:35.177 --> 01:07:37.179
But I can't have a blueberry
as a daughter.

687
01:07:37.346 --> 01:07:38.931
How is she supposed to compete?

688
01:07:39.097 --> 01:07:40.515
You could put her in a county fair.

689
01:07:54.821 --> 01:07:56.823
<i>Yeah. yeah</i>

690
01:08:01.453 --> 01:08:02.913
<i>Yeah</i>

691
01:08:03.080 --> 01:08:05.249
<i>Listen close. and listen hard</i>

692
01:08:05.415 --> 01:08:07.292
<i>To the tale of Violet Beauregarde</i>

693
01:08:07.459 --> 01:08:10.003
<i>This gentle girl
She sees no wrong</i>

694
01:08:10.170 --> 01:08:12.589
<i>In chewing. chewing. chewing. chewing</i>

695
01:08:12.756 --> 01:08:14.967
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

696
01:08:15.133 --> 01:08:17.135
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

697
01:08:17.344 --> 01:08:19.846
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

698
01:08:20.013 --> 01:08:22.140
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

699
01:08:23.642 --> 01:08:24.977
<i>Yeah</i>

700
01:08:34.236 --> 01:08:36.530
<i>She goes on chewing till. at last</i>

701
01:08:36.697 --> 01:08:38.824
<i>Her chewing muscles grow so vast</i>

702
01:08:38.991 --> 01:08:41.326
<i>And from her face
Her giant chin</i>

703
01:08:41.493 --> 01:08:43.829
<i>Sticks out just like a violin</i>

704
01:08:43.996 --> 01:08:46.164
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

705
01:08:46.373 --> 01:08:48.500
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

706
01:08:48.667 --> 01:08:51.003
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

707
01:08:55.507 --> 01:08:57.843
<i>For years and years she chews away</i>

708
01:08:58.010 --> 01:09:00.345
<i>Her jaws get stronger every day</i>

709
01:09:00.512 --> 01:09:02.681
<i>And with one great. tremendous chew</i>

710
01:09:02.889 --> 01:09:05.058
<i>They bite the poor girl's tongue in two</i>

711
01:09:05.392 --> 01:09:07.394
<i>And that is why we try so hard</i>

712
01:09:07.894 --> 01:09:10.147
<i>To save Miss Violet Beauregarde</i>

713
01:09:10.314 --> 01:09:12.524
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

714
