<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

715
01:09:15.068 --> 01:09:17.362
<i>Chewing. chewing. chewing. chewing</i>

716
01:09:17.529 --> 01:09:20.032
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

717
01:09:20.198 --> 01:09:22.200
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

718
01:09:22.409 --> 01:09:24.661
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

719
01:09:24.828 --> 01:09:26.204
<i>Chewing. chewing all day long</i>

720
01:09:26.413 --> 01:09:28.540
Mr. Wonka!

721
01:09:33.920 --> 01:09:36.381
I want you to roll Miss Beauregarde
into the boat...

722
01:09:37.090 --> 01:09:40.302
...and take her along to
the Juicing Room at once. okay?

723
01:09:40.927 --> 01:09:43.430
Juicing Room?
What are they gonna do to her there?

724
01:09:44.014 --> 01:09:45.724
They're gonna squeeze her.

725
01:09:45.932 --> 01:09:47.851
Like a little pimple.

726
01:09:48.727 --> 01:09:51.730
We gotta squeeze all that juice
out of her immediately.

727
01:09:55.025 --> 01:09:56.568
Mother. help me.

728
01:09:56.735 --> 01:09:58.445
Please.

729
01:10:03.533 --> 01:10:05.202
Come on.

730
01:10:05.702 --> 01:10:06.787
Let's boogie.

731
01:10:07.454 --> 01:10:10.582
Without the boat. we'll have to move
double-time to keep on schedule.

732
01:10:10.749 --> 01:10:12.042
There's too much to see.

733
01:10:12.209 --> 01:10:13.251
- Mr. Wonka?
- Yeah?

734
01:10:13.543 --> 01:10:15.253
Why did you decide to let people in?

735
01:10:15.504 --> 01:10:17.464
So they could see the factory.
of course.

736
01:10:17.672 --> 01:10:20.050
But why now? And why only five?

737
01:10:20.217 --> 01:10:22.511
What's the special prize.
and who gets it?

738
01:10:22.677 --> 01:10:24.554
The best kind of prize is a surprise.

739
01:10:26.139 --> 01:10:28.058
Will Violet always be a blueberry?

740
01:10:28.225 --> 01:10:30.310
No. Maybe. I don't know.

741
01:10:30.644 --> 01:10:33.605
That's what you get from chewing gum
all day. It's disgusting.

742
01:10:33.855 --> 01:10:36.149
If you hate gum so much.
why do you make it?

743
01:10:36.316 --> 01:10:39.277
Once again. you shouldn't mumble.
It's starting to bum me out.

744
01:10:39.486 --> 01:10:42.364
Can you remember the first candy
you ever ate?

745
01:10:45.992 --> 01:10:47.202
No.

746
01:10:47.369 --> 01:10:49.371
<i>In fact. Willy Wonka did remember...</i>

747
01:10:49.538 --> 01:10:53.542
<i>...the first candy he ever ate.</i>

748
01:11:53.560 --> 01:11:56.813
I'm sorry. I was having a flashback.

749
01:11:57.439 --> 01:11:59.191
I see.

750
01:11:59.566 --> 01:12:01.485
These flashbacks happen often?

751
01:12:01.651 --> 01:12:03.612
Increasingly...

752
01:12:03.904 --> 01:12:05.238
...today.

753
01:12:12.579 --> 01:12:14.789
Ah. this is a room I know all about.

754
01:12:14.956 --> 01:12:18.084
For you see. Mr. Wonka.
I. myself. am in the nut business.

755
01:12:18.251 --> 01:12:21.671
Are you using the Havermax 4000
to do your sorting?

756
01:12:21.838 --> 01:12:23.465
No.

757
01:12:23.632 --> 01:12:25.091
You're really weird.

758
01:12:46.404 --> 01:12:49.115
- Squirrels.
- Yeah. Squirrels.

759
01:12:49.282 --> 01:12:52.536
These squirrels are specially trained
to get the nuts out of shells.

760
01:13:08.927 --> 01:13:11.429
Why use squirrels?
Why not use Oompa-Loompas?

761
01:13:11.638 --> 01:13:16.142
Because only squirrels can get the whole
walnut out almost every single time.

762
01:13:16.726 --> 01:13:19.938
See how they tap them with their
knuckles to make sure it's not bad?

763
01:13:20.355 --> 01:13:21.648
Oh. look. Look.

764
01:13:23.400 --> 01:13:24.985
I think that one's got a bad nut.

765
01:13:27.362 --> 01:13:29.072
Daddy. I want a squirrel.

766
01:13:29.239 --> 01:13:31.449
Get me one of those squirrels.
I want one.

767
01:13:31.908 --> 01:13:34.452
Veruca. dear.
you have many marvelous pets.

768
01:13:34.661 --> 01:13:38.623
All I've got at home is one pony and
two dogs and four cats and six rabbits...

769
01:13:38.790 --> 01:13:42.335
...and two parakeets and three canaries
and a green parrot and a turtle...

770
01:13:42.502 --> 01:13:45.672
...and a silly old hamster.
I want a squirrel!

771
01:13:46.089 --> 01:13:47.340
All right. pet.

772
01:13:47.507 --> 01:13:50.218
Daddy will get you a squirrel
as soon as he possibly can.

773
01:13:50.385 --> 01:13:53.930
But I don't want any old squirrel.
I want a trained squirrel.

774
01:13:55.265 --> 01:13:56.850
Very well.

775
01:13:57.183 --> 01:14:00.353
Mr. Wonka. how much do you want
for one of these squirrels?

776
01:14:00.520 --> 01:14:02.480
Name your price.

777
01:14:03.356 --> 01:14:05.984
Oh. they're not for sale.
She can't have one.

778
01:14:10.989 --> 01:14:12.574
Daddy.

779
01:14:14.242 --> 01:14:15.493
I'm sorry. darling.

780
01:14:15.952 --> 01:14:18.121
Mr. Wonka's being unreasonable.

781
01:14:20.749 --> 01:14:24.294
If you won't get me a squirrel.
I'll get one myself.

782
01:14:33.219 --> 01:14:34.596
Veruca.

783
01:14:36.222 --> 01:14:37.599
Little girl?

784
01:14:41.394 --> 01:14:43.229
Veruca. come back here at once.

785
01:14:45.857 --> 01:14:47.484
Veruca.

786
01:14:59.371 --> 01:15:00.789
Little girl?

787
01:15:01.289 --> 01:15:03.041
Don't touch that squirrel's nuts.

788
01:15:03.249 --> 01:15:05.335
It'll make him crazy.

789
01:15:21.643 --> 01:15:23.103
I'll have you.

790
01:15:28.358 --> 01:15:29.776
Veruca.

791
01:15:36.074 --> 01:15:37.409
Veruca.

792
01:15:39.619 --> 01:15:41.162
No!

793
01:15:45.542 --> 01:15:46.918
Veruca!

794
01:15:49.087 --> 01:15:51.423
Let's find the key.

795
01:15:52.882 --> 01:15:54.217
Nope. Not that one.

796
01:15:55.301 --> 01:15:57.554
- Daddy!
- Veruca!

797
01:15:58.555 --> 01:16:00.807
No. It's not that one.

798
01:16:12.360 --> 01:16:14.112
There it is.

799
01:16:14.320 --> 01:16:15.488
There it isn't.

800
01:16:15.655 --> 01:16:17.407
Daddy. I want them to stop.

801
01:16:28.126 --> 01:16:29.586
What are they doing?

802
01:16:29.753 --> 01:16:31.755
They're testing to see
if she's a bad nut.

803
01:16:33.840 --> 01:16:36.634
Oh. my goodness.
She is a bad nut after all.

804
01:16:43.850 --> 01:16:45.143
Veruca!

805
01:16:45.727 --> 01:16:47.103
Daddy!

806
01:16:47.270 --> 01:16:48.813
Where are they taking her?

807
01:16:48.980 --> 01:16:51.775
Where all the other bad nuts go.
To the garbage chute.

808
01:16:53.276 --> 01:16:55.528
- Where does the chute go?
- To the incinerator.

809
01:16:56.362 --> 01:16:58.698
But don't worry.
We only light it on Tuesdays.

810
01:16:58.865 --> 01:17:00.492
Today is Tuesday.

811
01:17:02.660 --> 01:17:05.705
There's always the chance
they decided not to light it today.

812
01:17:15.548 --> 01:17:17.008
- Ah!
- Ah!

813
01:17:24.057 --> 01:17:27.018
Now. she may be stuck in the chute
just below the top.

814
01:17:27.185 --> 01:17:30.814
If that's the case. all you have to do
is just reach in and pull her out.

815
01:17:31.689 --> 01:17:32.899
Okay?

816
01:18:10.937 --> 01:18:14.065
<i>Veruca Salt. the little brute</i>

817
01:18:14.232 --> 01:18:17.360
<i>Has just gone down the garbage chute</i>

818
01:18:17.527 --> 01:18:21.614
<i>And she will meet. as she descends</i>

819
01:18:21.781 --> 01:18:25.034
<i>A rather different set of friends</i>

820
01:18:25.201 --> 01:18:28.121
<i>A rather different set of friends</i>

821
01:18:28.288 --> 01:18:31.958
<i>A rather different set of friends</i>

822
01:18:32.125 --> 01:18:35.253
<i>A fish head. for example. cut</i>

823
01:18:35.461 --> 01:18:38.506
<i>This morning from a halibut</i>

824
01:18:38.673 --> 01:18:41.926
<i>An oyster from an oyster stew</i>

825
01:18:42.093 --> 01:18:45.847
<i>A steak that no one else would chew</i>

826
01:18:46.014 --> 01:18:49.350
<i>And lots of other things as well</i>

827
01:18:49.517 --> 01:18:55.648
<i>Each with its rather horrid smell</i>

828
01:18:55.815 --> 01:18:59.569
<i>Horrid smell</i>

829
01:18:59.903 --> 01:19:03.114
<i>These are Veruca's newfound friends</i>

830
01:19:03.281 --> 01:19:06.826
<i>That she will meet as she descends</i>

831
01:19:06.993 --> 01:19:12.248
<i>These are Veruca's newfound friends</i>

832
01:19:31.351 --> 01:19:34.896
<i>Who went and spoiled her. who indeed?</i>

833
01:19:35.063 --> 01:19:38.483
<i>Who pandered to her every need?</i>

834
01:19:38.650 --> 01:19:41.861
<i>Who turned her into such a brat?</i>

835
01:19:42.028 --> 01:19:43.821
<i>Who are the culprits?</i>

836
01:19:44.030 --> 01:19:45.490
<i>Who did that?</i>

837
01:19:45.657 --> 01:19:48.952
<i>The guilty ones. now this is sad</i>

838
01:19:49.243 --> 01:19:52.830
<i>Are dear old Mum and loving Dad</i>

839
01:19:53.748 --> 01:19:54.832
Ah!

840
01:20:03.383 --> 01:20:05.677
Oh. really? Oh. good.

841
01:20:05.885 --> 01:20:08.429
I've just been informed
that the incinerator's broken.

842
01:20:08.596 --> 01:20:12.183
So there should be about three weeks
of rotten garbage to break their fall.

843
01:20:12.350 --> 01:20:13.851
Well. that's good news.

844
01:20:14.143 --> 01:20:15.645
Yeah.

845
01:20:16.145 --> 01:20:18.898
Well. let's keep on trucking.

846
01:20:21.567 --> 01:20:23.778
I don't know why
I didn't think of this earlier.

847
01:20:23.945 --> 01:20:27.156
The elevator's by far the most
efficient way to get around the factory.

848
01:20:27.323 --> 01:20:29.158
There can't be this many floors.

849
01:20:30.076 --> 01:20:32.161
How do you know. Mr. Smarty-Pants?

850
01:20:32.328 --> 01:20:35.081
This isn't an ordinary
up-and-down elevator. by the way.

851
01:20:35.248 --> 01:20:37.750
This elevator can go sideways.
longways. slantways...

852
01:20:37.917 --> 01:20:39.544
...and any other ways
you can think of.

853
01:20:39.711 --> 01:20:42.588
You just press any button
and. whoosh. you're off.

854
01:20:52.765 --> 01:20:54.100
Oh. look. Look.

855
01:20:55.351 --> 01:20:58.438
Ladies and gentlemen.
welcome to Fudge Mountain.

856
01:21:21.044 --> 01:21:22.378
Oh.

857
01:21:27.467 --> 01:21:29.260
I'd rather not talk about this one.

858
01:21:40.646 --> 01:21:42.774
This is the Puppet Hospital
and Burn Center.

859
01:21:47.320 --> 01:21:50.156
It's relatively new.

860
01:21:56.788 --> 01:21:58.289
Ah. the administration offices.

861
01:22:00.458 --> 01:22:01.876
Hello. Doris.

862
01:22:37.203 --> 01:22:39.997
Why is everything here
completely pointless?

863
01:22:40.206 --> 01:22:42.166
Candy doesn't have to have a point.

864
01:22:42.333 --> 01:22:43.668
That's why it's candy.

865
01:22:43.835 --> 01:22:45.336
It's stupid.

866
01:22:45.878 --> 01:22:49.090
Candy is a waste of time.

867
01:22:49.715 --> 01:22:52.969
No son of mine is going to be
a chocolatier.

868
01:22:53.511 --> 01:22:55.054
Then I'll run away.

869
01:22:55.221 --> 01:22:57.348
To Switzerland. Bavaria.

870
01:22:57.598 --> 01:22:59.517
The candy capitals of the world.

871
01:23:00.226 --> 01:23:01.561
Go ahead.

872
01:23:01.727 --> 01:23:03.563
But I won't be here
when you come back.

873
01:23:32.133 --> 01:23:33.426
Sorry. son.

874
01:23:33.593 --> 01:23:36.095
We're closing for the night.

875
01:24:01.537 --> 01:24:03.206
I wanna pick a room.

876
01:24:06.292 --> 01:24:07.710
Go ahead.

877
01:24:26.562 --> 01:24:27.855
Here.

878
01:24:28.314 --> 01:24:31.234
Put these on quick. and don't
take them off whatever you do.

879
01:24:31.901 --> 01:24:34.820
This light could burn your eyeballs
right out of your skulls.

880
01:24:35.154 --> 01:24:38.115
And we certainly don't want that.
now. do we?

881
01:24:40.952 --> 01:24:44.664
This is the testing room for my
very latest and greatest invention:

882
01:24:45.081 --> 01:24:47.541
Television Chocolate.

883
01:24:47.708 --> 01:24:48.960
One day it occurred to me:

884
01:24:49.126 --> 01:24:51.712
"Hey. if television can break up
a photograph...

885
01:24:51.879 --> 01:24:55.925
...into millions and millions of tiny pieces
and send it whizzing through the air...

886
01:24:56.092 --> 01:24:58.010
...then reassemble it
on the other end...

887
01:24:58.177 --> 01:25:00.179
...why can't I do the same
with chocolate?

888
01:25:00.638 --> 01:25:03.474
Why can't I send a real bar
of chocolate...

889
01:25:03.641 --> 01:25:06.018
...through the television.
all ready to be eaten?"

890
01:25:06.185 --> 01:25:09.939
<i>I'm not gonna touch it.
I'm not going in that direction.</i>

891
01:25:11.357 --> 01:25:12.608
Sounds impossible.

892
01:25:13.067 --> 01:25:14.402
It is impossible.

893
01:25:15.361 --> 01:25:18.030
You don't understand anything
about science.

894
01:25:18.197 --> 01:25:23.286
First off. there's a difference between
waves and particles. Duh.

895
01:25:23.452 --> 01:25:27.039
Second. the amount of power it
would take to convert energy in matter...

896
01:25:27.373 --> 01:25:29.000
...would be like nine atomic bombs.

897
01:25:29.208 --> 01:25:30.668
Mumbler!

898
01:25:31.502 --> 01:25:35.506
Seriously. I cannot understand
a single word you're saying.

899
01:25:39.093 --> 01:25:40.553
Okey-dokey.

900
01:25:40.720 --> 01:25:44.056
I shall now send a bar of chocolate
from one end of the room...

901
01:25:44.223 --> 01:25:47.310
...to the other by television.

902
01:25:47.476 --> 01:25:48.894
Bring in the chocolate.

903
01:26:09.665 --> 01:26:12.335
It's gotta be real big
because you know how on TV...

904
01:26:12.501 --> 01:26:15.880
...you can film a regular-size man.
and he comes out looking this tall?

905
01:26:16.047 --> 01:26:17.465
Same basic principle.

906
01:26:49.455 --> 01:26:51.040
It's gone.

907
01:26:51.999 --> 01:26:56.128
Told you. That chocolate is now rushing
through the air above our heads...

908
01:26:56.295 --> 01:26:58.756
...in a million tiny little pieces.

909
01:26:58.964 --> 01:27:01.801
Come over here.
Come on. Come on. Come on!

910
01:27:07.390 --> 01:27:09.141
Watch the screen.

911
01:27:12.520 --> 01:27:14.146
Here it comes.

912
01:27:15.231 --> 01:27:16.816
Oh. look.

913
01:27:20.903 --> 01:27:23.614
- Take it.
- It's just a picture on a screen.

914
01:27:24.573 --> 01:27:25.825
Scaredy-cat.

915
01:27:25.991 --> 01:27:27.493
You take it.

916
01:27:28.327 --> 01:27:30.621
Go on. Just reach out and grab it.

917
01:27:38.796 --> 01:27:40.297
Go on.

918
01:27:48.305 --> 01:27:50.141
Holy buckets.

919
01:27:53.144 --> 01:27:55.271
Eat it. Go on.

920
01:27:55.438 --> 01:27:57.606
It'll be delicious. It's the same bar.

921
01:27:57.773 --> 01:28:01.068
It's just gotten a little smaller
on the journey. that's all.

922
01:28:09.410 --> 01:28:10.911
It's great.

923
01:28:11.078 --> 01:28:12.455
It's a miracle.

924
01:28:14.248 --> 01:28:17.084
So imagine. you're sitting at home
watching television...

925
01:28:17.251 --> 01:28:21.005
...and suddenly a commercial will flash
onto the screen. and a voice will say:

926
01:28:21.172 --> 01:28:25.259
"Wonka's chocolates
are the best in the world.

927
01:28:25.426 --> 01:28:28.345
If you don't believe us.
try one for yourself."

928
01:28:29.346 --> 01:28:32.933
And you simply reach out and take it.

929
01:28:33.851 --> 01:28:35.144
How about that?

930
01:28:35.311 --> 01:28:37.229
So can you send other things?

931
01:28:37.396 --> 01:28:39.190
Say. like. breakfast cereal?

932
01:28:39.565 --> 01:28:42.151
Do you have any idea
what breakfast cereal's made of?

933
01:28:42.318 --> 01:28:45.654
It's those little curly wooden shavings
you find in pencil sharpeners.

934
01:28:45.821 --> 01:28:47.948
But could you send it by TV
if you wanted to?

935
01:28:48.240 --> 01:28:50.242
- Of course I could.
- What about people?

936
01:28:50.618 --> 01:28:54.121
Well. why would I wanna send a person?
They don't taste very good at all.

937
01:28:54.288 --> 01:28:57.500
Don't you realize what you've invented?
It's a teleporter.

938
01:28:57.708 --> 01:29:00.669
It's the most important invention
in the history of the world.

939
01:29:00.836 --> 01:29:03.005
And all you think about is chocolate.

940
01:29:03.172 --> 01:29:04.381
Calm down. Mike.

941
01:29:04.590 --> 01:29:07.343
I think Mr. Wonka knows
what he's talking about.

942
01:29:07.510 --> 01:29:09.929
No. he doesn't. He has no idea.

943
01:29:10.095 --> 01:29:12.223
You think he's a genius.
but he's an idiot.

944
01:29:13.140 --> 01:29:14.892
But I'm not.

945
01:29:19.605 --> 01:29:21.106
Hey. little boy.

946
01:29:22.399 --> 01:29:24.109
Don't push my button.

947
01:30:05.526 --> 01:30:06.944
He's gone.

948
01:30:07.361 --> 01:30:09.905
Let's go check the television.
see what we get.

949
01:30:11.073 --> 01:30:13.450
I sure hope no part of him
gets left behind.

950
01:30:13.659 --> 01:30:14.868
What do you mean?

951
01:30:15.327 --> 01:30:19.748
Well. sometimes only half of
the little pieces find their way through.

952
01:30:20.916 --> 01:30:24.378
If you had to choose only one half
of your son. which one would it be?

953
01:30:24.670 --> 01:30:26.589
What kind of a question is that?

954
01:30:27.381 --> 01:30:30.467
No need to snap. Just a question.

955
01:30:31.302 --> 01:30:34.263
Try every channel.
I'm starting to feel a little anxious.

956
01:30:39.893 --> 01:30:41.687
- There he is.
- Mike.

957
01:30:42.354 --> 01:30:44.064
<i>The most important thing</i>

958
01:30:44.231 --> 01:30:45.482
<i>That we've ever learned</i>

959
01:30:45.691 --> 01:30:49.028
<i>The most important thing we've learned
As far as children are concerned</i>

960
01:30:49.194 --> 01:30:52.031
<i>Is never. never let them near
The television set</i>

961
01:30:52.197 --> 01:30:55.701
<i>Or better still just don't install
The idiotic thing at all</i>

962
01:30:56.702 --> 01:30:59.371
<i>Never. never let them
Never. never let them</i>

963
01:31:12.468 --> 01:31:14.053
<i>Never. never let them</i>

964
01:31:14.219 --> 01:31:15.512
<i>Never. never let them</i>

965
01:31:15.679 --> 01:31:17.473
<i>It rots the senses in the head</i>

966
01:31:17.640 --> 01:31:18.849
<i>It keeps imagination dead</i>

967
01:31:19.016 --> 01:31:20.517
<i>It clogs and clutters up the mind</i>

968
01:31:20.726 --> 01:31:22.311
<i>It makes a child so dull and blind</i>

969
01:31:22.478 --> 01:31:23.854
<i>So dull. so dull</i>

970
01:31:24.021 --> 01:31:27.024
<i>He can no longer understand
A fairy tale. a fairyland</i>

971
01:31:27.232 --> 01:31:28.776
<i>A fairyland. a fairyland</i>

972
01:31:28.984 --> 01:31:30.361
<i>His brain becomes as soft as cheese</i>

973
01:31:30.527 --> 01:31:32.029
<i>His thinking powers rust and freeze</i>

974
01:31:32.237 --> 01:31:35.449
<i>He cannot think. he only sees</i>

975
01:31:40.245 --> 01:31:43.207
<i>Regarding little Mike Teavee</i>

976
01:31:43.374 --> 01:31:46.001
<i>We very much regret that we</i>

977
01:31:46.543 --> 01:31:48.170
<i>Regret that we</i>

978
01:31:49.838 --> 01:31:51.423
<i>Shall simply have to wait and see</i>

979
01:31:51.590 --> 01:31:52.883
<i>Wait and see. wait and see</i>

980
01:31:53.050 --> 01:31:55.386
<i>Wait and see. wait and see. wait and see</i>

981
01:31:55.552 --> 01:31:56.887
<i>We very much regret that we</i>

982
01:31:57.054 --> 01:31:58.722
<i>Shall simply have to wait and see</i>

983
01:31:58.889 --> 01:32:00.724
<i>If we can get him back his height</i>

984
01:32:00.891 --> 01:32:03.477
<i>But if we can't</i>

985
01:32:03.644 --> 01:32:04.687
<i>It serves him right</i>

986
01:32:04.853 --> 01:32:06.397
Ew. somebody grab him.

987
01:32:06.563 --> 01:32:08.399
<i>Help me.</i>

988
01:32:09.108 --> 01:32:10.693
<i>Help me.</i>

989
01:32:11.610 --> 01:32:14.738
Oh. thank heavens.
He's completely unharmed.

990
01:32:14.905 --> 01:32:18.450
Unharmed?
What are you talking about?

991
01:32:21.286 --> 01:32:23.706
Just put me back in the other way.

992
01:32:23.872 --> 01:32:25.416
There is no other way.

993
01:32:25.582 --> 01:32:28.627
It's television. not telephone.
There's quite a difference.

994
01:32:28.836 --> 01:32:31.839
And what exactly do you propose
to do about it?

995
01:32:32.005 --> 01:32:33.090
I don't know.

996
01:32:34.049 --> 01:32:37.720
But young men are extremely springy.
They stretch like mad.

997
01:32:38.345 --> 01:32:41.432
- Let's go put him in the taffy puller.
- Taffy puller?

998
01:32:42.099 --> 01:32:43.434
Hey. that was my idea.

999
01:32:45.561 --> 01:32:46.937
Boy. is he gonna be skinny.

1000
01:32:47.980 --> 01:32:49.565
Yeah.

1001
01:32:49.732 --> 01:32:51.984
Taffy puller.

1002
01:32:52.985 --> 01:32:55.446
I want you to take Mr. Teavee
and his...

1003
01:32:56.822 --> 01:32:59.450
...little boy up to
the taffy puller. okay?

1004
01:32:59.616 --> 01:33:01.410
Stretch him out.

1005
01:33:12.212 --> 01:33:14.131
On with the tour.

1006
01:33:23.015 --> 01:33:25.309
There's still so much left to see.

1007
01:33:25.476 --> 01:33:28.020
Now. how many children are left?

1008
01:33:30.731 --> 01:33:35.152
Mr. Wonka.
Charlie's the only one left now.

1009
01:33:37.404 --> 01:33:38.864
You mean. you're the only one?

1010
01:33:39.782 --> 01:33:41.450
Yes.

1011
01:33:41.658 --> 01:33:42.993
What happened to the others?

1012
01:33:47.539 --> 01:33:50.167
Oh. my dear boy.
but that means you've won.

1013
01:33:50.375 --> 01:33:52.503
Oh. I do congratulate you. I really do.

1014
01:33:52.669 --> 01:33:54.004
I'm absolutely delighted.

1015
01:33:54.171 --> 01:33:56.715
I had a hunch right from the beginning.
Well done.

1016
01:33:56.882 --> 01:33:58.884
Now. we mustn't dilly or dally.

1017
01:33:59.051 --> 01:34:02.095
We have an enormous number
of things to do before the day's out.

1018
01:34:02.262 --> 01:34:06.225
But luckily for us. we have the great
glass elevator to speed things along--

1019
01:34:12.689 --> 01:34:13.982
Speed things along.

1020
01:34:16.819 --> 01:34:18.403
Come on.

1021
01:34:24.618 --> 01:34:26.912
"Up and Out"?
What kind of room is that?

1022
01:34:27.454 --> 01:34:29.122
Hold on.

1023
01:34:37.923 --> 01:34:39.550
Oh. my goodness.

1024
01:34:39.716 --> 01:34:43.387
We're gonna need to go much faster.
otherwise we'll just never break through.

1025
01:34:43.554 --> 01:34:45.097
Break through what?

1026
01:34:45.347 --> 01:34:47.766
I've been longing to press
that button for years.

1027
01:34:48.517 --> 01:34:51.270
Well. here we go. Up and out.

1028
01:34:51.603 --> 01:34:54.022
- But do you really mean--?
- Yeah. I do.

1029
01:34:54.189 --> 01:34:55.691
But it's made of glass.

1030
01:34:55.858 --> 01:34:57.860
It'll smash into a million pieces.

1031
01:35:33.478 --> 01:35:36.398
Augustus. please
don't eat your fingers.

1032
01:35:36.565 --> 01:35:38.483
But I taste so good.

1033
01:35:51.622 --> 01:35:54.082
Look. Mother.
I'm much more flexible now.

1034
01:35:54.625 --> 01:35:57.127
Yes. but you're blue.

1035
01:36:19.608 --> 01:36:22.319
Daddy. I want a flying glass elevator.

1036
01:36:22.945 --> 01:36:26.406
Veruca. the only thing you're getting
today is a bath. and that's final.

1037
01:36:26.573 --> 01:36:28.200
But I want it.

1038
01:36:45.175 --> 01:36:47.052
Where do you live?

1039
01:36:47.886 --> 01:36:50.055
Right over there. That little house.

1040
01:36:55.352 --> 01:36:57.187
What time do you think
they'll be back?

1041
01:36:57.354 --> 01:36:59.064
Hard to know. dear.

1042
01:37:10.701 --> 01:37:13.328
I think there's someone at the door.

1043
01:37:13.495 --> 01:37:15.288
Hi. Mom.

1044
01:37:17.833 --> 01:37:20.085
Mom. Dad. We're back.

1045
01:37:20.252 --> 01:37:21.920
- Charlie.
- Charlie.

1046
01:37:23.296 --> 01:37:24.881
Goodness.

1047
01:37:26.717 --> 01:37:29.428
This is Willy Wonka.
He gave us a ride home.

1048
01:37:29.886 --> 01:37:31.304
I see that.

1049
01:37:31.471 --> 01:37:33.473
You must be the boy's--

1050
01:37:34.766 --> 01:37:37.310
- Parents?
- Yeah. That.

1051
01:37:37.477 --> 01:37:40.397
He says Charlie's won something.

1052
01:37:41.857 --> 01:37:43.233
Not just some something.

1053
01:37:43.608 --> 01:37:47.529
The most "something" something
of any something that's ever been.

1054
01:37:48.030 --> 01:37:50.866
I'm gonna give this little boy
my entire factory.

1055
01:37:52.993 --> 01:37:55.078
You must be joking.

1056
01:37:55.245 --> 01:37:56.538
No. really. It's true.

1057
01:37:56.705 --> 01:38:00.167
Because you see. a few months ago.
I was having my semiannual haircut...

1058
01:38:00.333 --> 01:38:03.628
...and I had the strangest revelation.

1059
01:38:17.434 --> 01:38:19.269
<i>In that one silver hair...</i>

1060
01:38:19.436 --> 01:38:21.980
<i>...I saw reflected my life's work...</i>

1061
01:38:22.147 --> 01:38:25.567
<i>...my factory.
my beloved Oompa-Loompas.</i>

1062
01:38:25.734 --> 01:38:28.653
<i>Who would watch over them
after I was gone?</i>

1063
01:38:28.820 --> 01:38:30.614
<i>I realized in that moment:</i>

1064
01:38:30.781 --> 01:38:33.283
I must find a heir.

1065
01:38:34.826 --> 01:38:36.953
And I did. Charlie.

1066
01:38:37.162 --> 01:38:38.497
You.

1067
01:38:40.707 --> 01:38:42.793
That's why you sent out
the golden tickets.

1068
01:38:43.418 --> 01:38:44.461
Uh-huh.

1069
01:38:44.669 --> 01:38:46.505
What are Oompa-Loompas?

1070
01:38:46.671 --> 01:38:48.673
I invited five children to the factory...

1071
01:38:48.840 --> 01:38:51.676
...and the one who was the least rotten
would be the winner.

1072
01:38:52.010 --> 01:38:53.470
That's you. Charlie.

1073
01:38:53.929 --> 01:38:55.388
So. what do you say?

1074
01:38:55.555 --> 01:38:59.226
Are you ready to leave all this behind
and come live with me at the factory?

1075
01:38:59.392 --> 01:39:00.644
Sure. Of course.

1076
01:39:00.811 --> 01:39:03.480
I mean. it's all right
if my family come too?

1077
01:39:03.688 --> 01:39:05.941
Oh. my dear boy. of course they can't.

1078
01:39:06.775 --> 01:39:08.485
You can't run a chocolate factory...

1079
01:39:08.693 --> 01:39:11.988
...with a family hanging over you
like an old. dead goose. No offense.

1080
01:39:12.197 --> 01:39:13.990
None taken. jerk.

1081
01:39:16.076 --> 01:39:18.578
A chocolatier has to run free and solo.

1082
01:39:18.745 --> 01:39:21.706
He has to follow his dreams.
Gosh darn the consequences.

1083
01:39:23.208 --> 01:39:24.459
Look at me.

1084
01:39:24.626 --> 01:39:27.212
I had no family.
and I'm a giant success.

1085
01:39:28.505 --> 01:39:32.509
So if I go with you to the factory.
I won't ever see my family again?

1086
01:39:32.717 --> 01:39:35.053
Yeah. Consider that a bonus.

1087
01:39:37.722 --> 01:39:38.890
Then I'm not going.

1088
01:39:40.016 --> 01:39:42.227
I wouldn't give up my family
for anything.

1089
01:39:43.061 --> 01:39:44.980
Not for all the chocolate in the world.

1090
01:39:47.524 --> 01:39:49.651
Oh. I see.

1091
01:39:51.528 --> 01:39:53.446
That's weird.

1092
01:39:56.575 --> 01:39:59.244
There's other candy too
besides chocolate.

1093
01:40:00.245 --> 01:40:03.081
I'm sorry. Mr. Wonka.
I'm staying here.

1094
01:40:05.876 --> 01:40:07.586
Wow.

1095
01:40:09.921 --> 01:40:11.756
Well. that's just...

1096
01:40:12.507 --> 01:40:14.467
...unexpected...

1097
01:40:16.052 --> 01:40:17.679
...and weird.

1098
01:40:24.769 --> 01:40:27.439
But I suppose. in that case. I'll just--

1099
01:40:29.858 --> 01:40:31.151
Goodbye. then.

1100
01:40:34.279 --> 01:40:35.780
Sure you won't change your mind?

1101
01:40:38.408 --> 01:40:39.951
I'm sure.

1102
01:40:49.294 --> 01:40:51.296
Okay. Bye.

1103
01:41:12.943 --> 01:41:15.695
Things are going to get much better.

1104
01:41:16.613 --> 01:41:19.366
<i>And for once. Grandma Georgina...</i>

1105
01:41:19.532 --> 01:41:22.327
<i>...knew exactly what
she was talking about.</i>

1106
01:41:23.078 --> 01:41:27.457
<i>The next morning. Charlie helped
his parents fix the hole in the roof.</i>

1107
01:41:28.917 --> 01:41:31.962
<i>Grandpa Joe spent the whole day
out of bed.</i>

1108
01:41:32.128 --> 01:41:33.964
<i>He didn't feel tired at all.</i>

1109
01:41:35.840 --> 01:41:39.344
<i>Charlie's father got a better job
at the toothpaste factory...</i>

1110
01:41:39.511 --> 01:41:43.056
<i>...repairing the machine
that had replaced him.</i>

1111
01:41:44.849 --> 01:41:48.186
<i>Things had never been better
for the Bucket family.</i>

1112
01:41:48.520 --> 01:41:52.107
<i>The same could not be said
for Willy Wonka.</i>

1113
01:41:52.274 --> 01:41:54.484
I can't put my finger on it.

1114
01:41:54.943 --> 01:41:57.195
Candy's the only thing
I was ever certain of...

1115
01:41:57.362 --> 01:41:59.823
...and now I'm just not
certain at all.

1116
01:41:59.990 --> 01:42:02.784
I don't know which flavors to make
or which ideas to try.

1117
01:42:02.951 --> 01:42:05.620
I'm second-guessing myself.
which is nuts.

1118
01:42:07.080 --> 01:42:10.166
I've always made whatever candy
I felt like. and I--

1119
01:42:16.464 --> 01:42:18.425
That's just it. isn't it?

1120
01:42:18.591 --> 01:42:23.138
I make the candy I feel like. but now
I feel terrible. so the candy's terrible.

1121
01:42:24.306 --> 01:42:26.891
You're very good.

1122
01:42:38.903 --> 01:42:40.822
Pity about that chocolate fellow.
Wendell-- Walter.

1123
01:42:42.532 --> 01:42:44.576
- Willy Wonka.
- That's the one.

1124
01:42:45.285 --> 01:42:48.330
Says here in the paper his new candies
aren't selling very well.

1125
01:42:48.913 --> 01:42:52.542
But I suppose maybe he's just
a rotten egg who deserves it.

1126
01:42:52.709 --> 01:42:55.587
- Yep.
- Oh. really?

1127
01:42:56.004 --> 01:42:58.048
You ever met him?

1128
01:42:58.214 --> 01:42:59.841
I did.

1129
01:43:00.008 --> 01:43:04.721
I thought he was great at first.
but then he didn't turn out so nice.

1130
01:43:05.430 --> 01:43:07.349
He also has a funny haircut.

1131
01:43:07.515 --> 01:43:08.850
I do not!

1132
01:43:09.851 --> 01:43:12.729
- Why are you here?
- I don't feel so hot.

1133
01:43:13.188 --> 01:43:15.565
What makes you feel better
when you feel terrible?

1134
01:43:15.940 --> 01:43:17.359
My family.

1135
01:43:17.525 --> 01:43:18.860
Ew.

1136
01:43:21.112 --> 01:43:22.947
What do you have against my family?

1137
01:43:23.698 --> 01:43:27.077
It's not just your family.
It's the whole idea of--

1138
01:43:30.372 --> 01:43:32.415
They tell you what to do.
what not to do...

1139
01:43:32.582 --> 01:43:35.043
...and it's not conducive
to a creative atmosphere.

1140
01:43:35.627 --> 01:43:39.464
Usually they're just trying to protect you
because they love you.

1141
01:43:41.466 --> 01:43:44.010
If you don't believe me.
you should ask.

1142
01:43:44.177 --> 01:43:47.138
Ask who? My father?

1143
01:43:47.555 --> 01:43:49.224
No way.

1144
01:43:50.392 --> 01:43:51.476
At least. not by myself.

1145
01:43:52.977 --> 01:43:54.270
You want me to go with you?

1146
01:43:56.481 --> 01:44:00.777
Hey. Hey. what a good idea. Yeah!

1147
01:44:03.488 --> 01:44:05.824
And you know what?
I've got transport--

1148
01:44:09.702 --> 01:44:12.997
I have to be more careful
where I park this thing.

1149
01:44:43.319 --> 01:44:45.864
I think we've got the wrong house.

1150
01:45:00.420 --> 01:45:01.880
Do you have an appointment?

1151
01:45:02.422 --> 01:45:04.549
No. But he's overdue.

1152
01:45:07.844 --> 01:45:09.846
Open.

1153
01:45:10.847 --> 01:45:15.768
Now. let's see what the damage is.
shall we?

1154
01:45:56.351 --> 01:45:57.852
Heavens.

1155
01:45:58.019 --> 01:46:01.189
I haven't seen bicuspids
like these since...

1156
01:46:05.235 --> 01:46:07.111
Since...

1157
01:46:16.329 --> 01:46:17.622
Willy?

1158
01:46:19.457 --> 01:46:20.917
Hi. Dad.

1159
01:46:31.928 --> 01:46:34.180
All these years...

1160
01:46:34.931 --> 01:46:37.058
...and you haven't flossed.

1161
01:46:39.143 --> 01:46:40.979
Not once.

1162
01:47:06.170 --> 01:47:07.589
<i>It was on this day...</i>

1163
01:47:07.797 --> 01:47:10.300
<i>...that Willy Wonka
repeated his offer to Charlie...</i>

1164
01:47:10.466 --> 01:47:13.219
<i>...who accepted on one condition.</i>

1165
01:47:13.386 --> 01:47:15.680
Sorry we're late.
We were brainstorming.

1166
01:47:15.847 --> 01:47:17.807
Thought I heard thunder.

1167
01:47:17.974 --> 01:47:21.603
- You staying for dinner. Willy?
- Yes. please.

1168
01:47:22.061 --> 01:47:24.188
I'll shuffle the plates.

1169
01:47:32.739 --> 01:47:36.034
You smell like peanuts.

1170
01:47:36.409 --> 01:47:39.787
- I love peanuts.
- Oh. thank you.

1171
01:47:39.954 --> 01:47:41.623
You smell like...

1172
01:47:41.789 --> 01:47:43.625
...old people and soap.

1173
01:47:46.502 --> 01:47:48.212
I like it.

1174
01:47:52.800 --> 01:47:55.303
Elbows off the table. Charlie.

1175
01:47:55.470 --> 01:47:57.847
How do you feel about
little raspberry kites?

1176
01:47:58.014 --> 01:47:59.557
With licorice instead of string.

1177
01:48:00.642 --> 01:48:04.145
- Boys. no business at the dinner table.
- Sorry. Mom.

1178
01:48:04.729 --> 01:48:07.732
I think you're on to something.
though. Charlie.

1179
01:48:19.494 --> 01:48:23.873
<i>In the end Charlie Bucket
won a chocolate factory.</i>

1180
01:48:25.249 --> 01:48:29.921
<i>But Willy Wonka got something
even better:</i>

1181
01:48:30.546 --> 01:48:33.049
<i>A family.</i>

1182
01:48:34.384 --> 01:48:38.554
<i>And one thing was absolutely certain:</i>

1183
01:48:38.971 --> 01:48:42.975
<i>Life had never been sweeter.</i>

1183
01:48:43.305 --> 01:49:43.650
